hive.org/web/20090517065859/http://www.giantslive.net/athletes_profiles.html |archivedate=May 17, 2009 |title=Athletes |website=Giants Live}}</ref> is an American professional [[strongman (strength athlete)|strongman]] competitor and winner of the [[2011 World's Strongest Man|2011]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/uncategorized/2011-worlds-strongest-man-winner/ |title=WSM 2011 Winner |website=The Worlds Strongest Man |date=January 15, 2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905025748/http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/uncategorized/2011-worlds-strongest-man-winner/ |archivedate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> [[2013 World's Strongest Man|2013]], [[2015 World's Strongest Man|2015]] and [[2016 World's Strongest Man]] competitions. Shaw is also the first man to have won the Arnold Strongman Classic and the World\u2019s Strongest Man contest in the same calendar year, a feat he accomplished in 2011 and then replicated in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arnoldstrongmanclassic.com/competitors.html |title=Athlete Biographies |website=The Arnold Strongman Classic |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822043556/http://www.arnoldstrongmanclassic.com/competitors.html |archivedate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShaw was born in [[Fort Lupton, Colorado]],<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news |last=Armstrong |first=Jim |url=http://www.denverpost.com/dontmiss/ci_12755582#ixzz0cVP9IG4H |title=Coloradan eyes coveted title of world's strongest man |newspaper=The Denver Post |date=July 4, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> the son of Jay and Bonnie Shaw.<ref name=\"post\"/> Both of his parents were taller than average, with his father standing at {{convert|6|ft|1|in|m|2|abbr=on}} and his mother {{convert|5|ft|11|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. It has been noted that he had uncles of exceptional stature.<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\nAt Fort Lupton High School, Shaw excelled in basketball.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shawstrengthshop.com/bio/brianshaw |title=Brian Shaw Bio |website=Shaw Strength |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004232225/http://www.shawstrengthshop.com/bio/brianshaw# |archive-date=October 4, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He then attended [[Otero Junior College]] in [[La Junta, Colorado]].<ref name=\"MovingOn\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ojc.edu/movingOn-MensBasketball.aspx |title=Men's Basketball: Moving On |website=Otero Junior College |date= |accessdate=October 26, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104025119/http://www.ojc.edu/movingOn-MensBasketball.aspx |archivedate=January 4, 2015}}</ref> There, he was able to form an inside combination with current Louisiana State University-Alexandria Head Women's Basketball Coach Bob Austin. Shaw was one of the team leaders for the Rattlers in his sophomore season. Following Otero, he went to [[Black Hills State University]] where he was on a full basketball scholarship<ref name=\"wsm\" /> and received a degree in wellness management.<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\nDuring his basketball career, Shaw was \"hooked on the weights\" and he has said that the weight room was his \"sanctuary\". In his own words, \"I've always been able to do this. The biggest tire, the heaviest stone... I've always been able to walk up and lift it. Odd strength is what it is, not weight-room strength. It's brute strength.\"<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===2005\u20132006===\nShaw began his career as a strongman with a win when he entered the Denver Strongest Man contest in October 2005. He had entered with no formal training. Just seven months later in June 2006 he joined the professional ranks and his successes continued.<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\n===2009===\nIn 2009 he entered [[Fortissimus]], otherwise known as the Strongest Man on Earth competition, in Canada where he came in third and was the only man to lift six Atlas stones weighing from {{convert|300|-|425|lb|kg|abbr=on}}. He then competed in Romania in the [[World Strongman Super Series]]. In September he travelled to his second [[World's Strongest Man]] contest in [[Valletta]]. There he was grouped in what was termed the \"group of death\" not least because of his presence in it. Alongside him in this group was [[Zydrunas Savickas]] who went on to win the title. Although Savickas won the group he and Shaw were separated by just two points. In the final Shaw went on to attain a podium finish, something Randell Strossen of [[Ironmind]] had predicted would happen when he said \"he has to be considered a favorite for a podium position. If he can stay healthy, there's no end to what he could do. He's got these gifts. He's the total package.\"<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\n===2010===\nShaw qualified for the finals at the [[2010 World's Strongest Man]] in [[Sun City, North West|Sun City]], [[South Africa]] in September 2010. He was tied for the lead at the end of the finals with [[Zydrunas Savickas]] and lost by countback, a system of scoring based on how the athletes placed in each event throughout the finals. Savickas had higher overall placings (2 first places and 1 second place out of 6 events) than Shaw (2 first places and 1 fourth place out of 6 events) and won the 2010 title.\n\nShaw competed against Savickas again in October 2010 at the [[Giants Live]] Istanbul contest. Shaw again finished second behind Savickas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/Oct/Giants_Live-Savickas_and_Shahlaei_Attack_the_Apollonxs_Axle.html |title=Giants Live: Savickas and Shahlaei Attack the Apollon's Axle |first=Randall J. |last=Strossen |website=[[IronMind]] |date=October 22, 2010 |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShaw won the inaugural [[J\u00f3n P\u00e1ll Sigmarsson Classic]] on November 21, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/Nov/Brian_Shaw_Wins_the_Inaugural_Jon_Pall_Sigmarsson_Classic_Strongman_Contest.html |title=Brian Shaw Wins the Inaugural Jon Pall Sigmarsson Classic Strongman Contest |first=Randall J. |last=Strossen |website=[[IronMind]] |date=November 22, 2010 |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShaw won the [[Strongman Super Series]] Swedish Grand Prix and became the 2010 overall Super Series champion on December 18, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/Dec/Brian_Shaw_Wins_World_Strongman_Super_Series_Swedish_Grand_Prix_and_Overall_Title.html |title=Brian Shaw Wins World Strongman Super Series Swedish Grand Prix and Overall Title |first=Randall J. |last=Strossen |website=[[IronMind]] |date=December 13, 2010 |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> This was Shaw's second consecutive overall Super Series championship.\n\n===2011-2013===\nIn 2011, Shaw once again participated in the World's Strongest man competition.  Going into the final event, the Atlas Stones, Shaw was tied with two-time champion Zydrunas Savickas.  Shaw beat Savickas taking 1st place.  In the 2013 competition, Shaw led Savickas into the final event (again the Atlas Stones) and again beat Savickas to win the competition.\n\n===2015\u20132016===\nShaw also won the 2015 and 2016 World's Strongest Man competitions.\n\n===2018===\n====2018 Arnold Strongman Classic====\nIn March 2018 Shaw competed in the 2018 Arnold Strongman Classic.  Shaw placed 2nd in Event One: The Bag Over Bar, 4th in Event Two: The Stone Shoulder, 2nd in Event Three: The Timber Carry, 3rd in Event Four: The Rogue Elephant Bar Deadlift, and was tied for 1st in Event Five: Apollon's Wheel leaving Shaw in 2nd place overall with 42 points to Bjornsson's 45.5<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roguefitness.com/2018-arnold-strongman-classic |title=The 2018 Arnold Strongman Classic |website=[[RogueFitness.com]] |date=March 3, 2018 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====World's Ultimate Strongman====\nIn October 2018 Shaw competed in the World\u2019s Ultimate Strongman competition in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://barbend.com/hafthor-bjornsson-worlds-ultimate-strongman/ |title=Hafthor Bjornsson Wins World's Ultimate Strongman, Walks Away With $75k |first=Jake |last=Boly |website=[[BarBend.com]] |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>  Shaw struggled with some of the events including the dead lift where he had trained with a different bar height and the yoke walk where the stage cracked under the combined weight of Shaw and the yoke, causing Shaw to briefly drop the yoke and increase his time.{{cn|date=December 2018}} Shaw still performed well, lifting all the objects in the overhead medley and was separated from Hafthor Bjornsson by less than one point going into the sixth and final event.  In the sixth and final event, the Atlas Stones, Shaw lifted all five stones but this was not enough to surpass Bjornsson in the final points tally, leaving Shaw in second place.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/hafthor-bjornsson-wins-worlds-ultimate-strongman-title-in-dubai |title=Hafthor Bjornsson wins World's Ultimate Strongman title in Dubai |first=Kelly |last=Clarke |website=[[Khaleej Times]] |date=October 27, 2018 |accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name                 = SHAWSTRENGTH\n| logo                 = \n| logo_caption         = \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| birth_name           = \n| birth_date           = \n| birth_place          = \n| death_date           = \n| death_place          = \n| nationality          = \n| occupation           = \n| website              = \n| pseudonym            = \n| channel_direct_url   = user/SHAWSTRENGTH/ \n| channel_display_name = SHAWSTRENGTH\n| years_active         = 2008-present\n| genre                = Weightlifting/Strength\n| subscribers          = 1.24 million\n| subscriber_date      = March 6, 2020\n| views                = 148.8 million\n| view_date            = March 6, 2020\n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n*[[Eddie Hall]]  \n*[[Nick Best]] \n*[[Robert Oberst]]\n*Jujimufu\n*[[Terry Hollands]]\n*Bradley Martyn\n| catchphrase(s)       = \n| silver_button        = yes\n| silver_year          = \n| gold_button          = yes\n| gold_year            = \n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = March 6, 2020 \n}}\n\nShaw has a [[YouTube channel]], SHAWSTRENGTH. He frequently uploads training footage (often with friends and other strongmen), fitness and strength challenges, and eating challenges. He is also active on the channel during competitions and often gives updates on his injuries.\n\nShaw also was one of four strongmen to be featured in the [[History Channel]] series, ''[[The Strongest Man in History]]'', which premiered on July 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Strongest Man in History Promo {{!}} Series Premiere Wed. July 10 at 10/9c {{!}} History |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C8wvh78nHls |website=YouTube |accessdate=October 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Brett |title=Brian Shaw and Eddie Hall Are Trying to Break the World's Most Legendary Strength Feats |url=https://www.menshealth.com/fitness/a28107056/strongest-man-in-history-trailer/ |accessdate=October 2, 2019 |work=Men's Health |date=June 19, 2019}}</ref> On the first episode of the show, he pulled a {{convert|12,000|lb|kg}} [[Viking ships|viking ship]] on a {{convert|60|ft|m}} incline course in 44.05 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Strongest Man in History: Pulling a 60,000 Pound Viking Ship (Season 1) {{!}} History |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=95OQvSTq97Y |website=History |accessdate=25 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Strongmen Show Off Viking Strength in Moorhead for HISTORY Show |url=https://www.kvrr.com/2019/07/08/strongmen-show-off-viking-strength-in-moorhead-for-history-show/ |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=KVRR Local News |date=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal records==\n'''Done in the gym'''\n* [[Squat (exercise)|Squat]] \u2013 {{cvt|903|lbs}}\n* [[Bench press]] \u2013 {{cvt|525|lbs}} &times; 2<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TLJzq3CNQ2Y|title=Worlds Strongest Man Brian Shaw - Training Highlights - Bench Press|website=[[YouTube]] |date=July 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* Deadlift \u2013 {{cvt|1025|lbs}}\n* Rack Pull - {{cvt|1365|lbs}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Brian Shaw Belt Squat Rack Pulls 1,365 Pounds for a Triple |url=https://barbend.com/brian-shaw-belt-squat-rack-pull/ |website=BarBend |author=Nick English |date=December 13, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n* Longbar Deadlift - {{cvt|1031|lbs}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Brian Shaw Long Bar Deadlifts 1031lb for an Unofficial World Record |url=https://barbend.com/brian-show-long-bar-deadlift/ |website=BarBend |author=Nick English |date=October 19, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Indoor Rower|Indoor Rowing]] \u2013 100 meters in 12.8&nbsp;seconds (unofficial world record at the time, since beaten by Loren Howard with 12.6)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SVl0Zt-kZys |title=World's Strongest Man Brian Shaw Takes 100M Rowing Record on a Whim |location=[[YouTube]] |date=September 15, 2016}}</ref>\n'''Grip training records'''\n* Little Big Horn Handle - {{cvt|238|lbs}} - previous record was {{cvt|236.53|lbs}} by Laine Snook<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8W8_sSSmgMc|title=EXTREME GRIP - NEW LITTLE BIG HORN RECORD 238LBS - BRIAN SHAW|website=[[YouTube]] |date=October 8, 2018 |accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Dinnie Stones|Dinnie Stone]] carry - {{cvt|11.54|ft}} <ref>{{cite web |last1=McAnally |first1=Ashlie |title=Strongman rocks up... for new world record! |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-scottish-mail-on-sunday/20190512/281947429293614 |website=pressreader.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Strongman'''\n''done in official Strongman competition''\n* Deadlift (with straps) \u2013 {{cvt|1014|lbs}} (World's Strongest Man 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/muscleprogympage/videos/1358985040803789/|title=Muscle PRO Gym|website=[[Facebook]]}}</ref>\n* Rogue Elephant Bar Deadlift (with straps) \u2013 {{cvt|1021|lbs}} (Arnold Strongman Classic 2016 & 2019)\n* Hummer Tire Strongman Deadlift (with straps) \u2013 {{cvt|1140|lbs}}<ref name=\"1140 lb tire deadlift\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7BQgZOek2OE |title=Brian Shaw 1140 Lb Tire Deadlift |website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n* Log Lift \u2013 {{cvt|440|lbs}}\n* Atlas Stone/Manhood Stone \u2013 {{cvt|560|lbs}} <ref>{{Citation|last=Rogue Fitness|title=2017 Rogue Record Breaker - Brian Shaw's 560lb Manhood Stone / 4K|date=March 6, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LFhZ5tPaCpc|accessdate=April 22, 2017|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n* [[Keg Toss]] \u2013 8 kegs in 16.59&nbsp;seconds (World's Strongest Man 2014).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://strongman.org/news/worlds-strongest-man-2014/ |title=World's Strongest Man 2014|website=Strongman.org|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* Keg Toss - 7.25m (World's Strongest Man 2016)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of strongmen]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brian Shaw (strongman)}}\n* {{IMDb name | 4743071 | Brian Shaw }}\n\n{{Footer - World's Strongest Man Champions}}\n{{Strongman Super Series World Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shaw, Brian}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportsmen]]\n[[Category:American strength athletes]]\n[[Category:Black Hills State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Weld County, Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "204.14.101.168", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIn other media)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Shaw_(strongman)"}
{"title_page": "Komodo (island)", "text_new": "{{Infobox islands\n|name = Komodo <br /> <small>[[New 7 Wonders of Nature]]</small>\n|image_name = Komodo Island north aerial.jpg\n|image_caption = Northern tip of the island\n|map_image = ID - Komodo.PNG\n|map_caption = \n|native_name = \n|native_name_link = \n|location = [[Southeast Asia]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|8.55|S|119.45|E|region:ID_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n|archipelago = [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n|total_islands = \n|major_islands = \n|area_km2 = 390\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m = \n|country = Indonesia\n|country_admin_divisions_title = Province\n|country_admin_divisions = [[East Nusa Tenggara]]\n|population = c. 2000\n|population_as_of = \n|density_km2 = \n|ethnic_groups = [[Buginese people|Bugis]], others\n}}\n\n'''Komodo''' ({{lang-id|Pulau Komodo}}) is one of the 17,508 [[Islands of Indonesia|islands]] that comprise the [[Indonesia|Republic of Indonesia]]. The island is particularly notable as the habitat of the [[Komodo dragon]], the largest lizard on Earth, which is named after the island. Komodo Island has a surface area of 390 square kilometres and a human population of over two thousand. The people of the island are descendants of former [[convict|convicts]] who were exiled to the island and who have mixed with [[Buginese people|Bugis]] from [[Sulawesi]]. The people are primarily adherents of [[Islam in Indonesia|Islam]] but there are also [[Christianity in Indonesia|Christian]] and [[Hinduism in Indonesia|Hindu]] congregations.\n\nKomodo is part of the [[Lesser Sunda Islands|Lesser Sunda chain]] of islands and forms part of the [[Komodo National Park]]. In addition, the island is a popular destination for [[Scuba diving|diving]]. Administratively, it is part of the [[East Nusa Tenggara]] [[Provinces of Indonesia|Province]].\n\n==Description==\nKomodo is part of the [[Lesser Sunda Islands|Lesser Sunda chain]] of islands and forms part of the [[Komodo National Park]]. It lies between the substantially larger neighboring islands [[Sumbawa]] to the west and [[Flores]] to the east. The island's surface area covers 390 square kilometres.  Komodo Island is home to the Komodo Dragon, the largest lizard on earth.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest stories (among Westerners) of a dragon-like animal existing in the region circulated widely and attracted considerable attention.  But no Westerner visited the island to check the story until official interest was sparked in the early 1910s by stories from [[Dutch people|Dutch]] sailors based in [[Flores]] in [[East Nusa Tenggara]] about a mysterious creature. The creature was allegedly a dragon which inhabited a small island in the Lesser Sunda Islands (the main island of which is Flores).\n[[Image:Vegetation on Komodo Island.jpg|thumb|right|Vegetation on Komodo Island]]\n\nThe Dutch sailors reported that the creature measured up to seven metres (twenty-three feet) in length with a large body and mouth which constantly breathed fire. It burnt them and so they could not continue the investigation. It was believed then that the odd creature could fly. Hearing the reports, Lieutenant Steyn van Hensbroek, an official of the Dutch Colonial Administration in Flores, planned a trip to Komodo Island to continue the search himself. He armed himself, and accompanied by a team of soldiers, he landed on the island. After a few days, Hensbroek managed to kill one of the lizards to investigate.\n\nVan Hensbroek took the dragon to headquarters where measurements were taken. It was approximately 2.1 metres (6.9 feet) long, with a shape very similar to that of a [[lizard]]. More samples were then photographed by Peter A. Ouwens, the Director of the Zoological Museum and [[Bogor Botanical Gardens|Botanical Gardens]] in [[Bogor]], [[Java]]. The records that Ouwens made are the first reliable documentation of details about what is now called the Komodo dragon (or Komodo monitor).\n\nOuwens was keen to obtain additional samples. He recruited hunters who killed two dragons measuring 3.1 metres and 3.35 metres as well as capturing two pups, each measuring less than one metre. Ouwens carried out studies on the samples and concluded that the Komodo dragon was not a flame-thrower but was a type of [[monitor lizard]]. Research results were published in 1912. Ouwens named the giant lizard ''Varanus komodoensis''. Realizing the significance of the dragons on Komodo Island as an endangered species, the Dutch government issued a regulation on the protection of the lizards on Komodo Island in 1915.\n\nThe Komodo dragon became something of a living legend. In the decades since the Komodo was discovered, various scientific expeditions from a range of countries have carried out field research on the dragons on Komodo Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indonesiaindonesia.com/f/37477-sejarah-pulau-komodo/|title=Sejarah Pulau Komodo|work=indonesiaindonesia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Modern day==\nKomodo has a human population of over two thousand, spread out over the island and in the main [[Komodo (village)|Komodo village]]. The native population of Komodo, the [[Komodo people]], has been extinct since the 1980s.<ref>[http://sains.kompas.com/read/2013/01/28/15514880/penduduk.hidup.bersama.komodo Penduduk Hidup Bersama Komodo]</ref> The present day people of the island are descendants of former [[convicts]] who were exiled to Komodo and who have mixed with [[Bugis]] from [[Sulawesi]]. The population is primarily adherents of [[Islam in Indonesia|Islam]] but there are also [[Christianity in Indonesia|Christian]] and [[Hinduism in Indonesia|Hindu]] congregations. Administratively, it is part of the [[East Nusa Tenggara]] [[Provinces of Indonesia|province]]. The island is also a popular destination for [[Scuba diving|diving]] and it has been included into the controversial [[New7Wonders of Nature]] list since November 11, 2011.\n\n'''Temporary closure of Komodo Island'''\n\nIn April 2019, Indonesian authorities announced a plan to close Komodo Island to tourism for a limited period to allow for conservation efforts amid concerns over animal-smuggling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/04/tourists-banned-from-home-of-komodo-dragon-as-smugglers-eye-dwindling-numbers|title=Komodo considers tourist ban to help boost dragon numbers|publisher=The Guardian|date=4 April 2019}}</ref>  In July 2019, it was confirmed that the island would be closed as from the beginning of 2020. The Governor of Nusa Tenggara Timur province, Viktor B. Laiskodat, said that a budget of Rp 100 billion (around $US 7.2 million) would be provided to support the conservation program.<ref>'[https://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2019/07/18/komodo-island-to-be-closed-in-2020-agency.html?src=mostviewed&pg=/ Komodo Island to be closed in 2020: Agency'], ''The Jakarta Post'', 18 July 2019.</ref> The plan is controversial: Governor Laiskodat has suggested that an expensive entrance fee be charged to foreign tourists while local villagers who live on Komodo Island are worried about the possible loss of income.<ref>Rebecca Henscheke and Callistasia Wijaya, '[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/extra/5bBE5791M9/The_fight_for_Dragon_Island The fight for Dragon Island'], ''BBC World'', 25 July 2019.</ref> \n\n===Fauna===\n[[Image:Kdki.jpg|thumb|right|Komodo dragon]]\n\nThe [[Komodo dragon]], the world's largest living lizard, takes its name from the island. A type of [[monitor lizard]], it inhabits Komodo Island and some of the smaller surrounding islands, as well as part of western Flores. [[Javan rusa|Javan deer]] also inhabit the island, though they are not native. Other animals include [[water buffalo]], [[banded pig]]s, civets, cockatoo and macaques.\n\n===Pink beach===\nKomodo contains a beach with \"[[pink]]\" [[sand]], one of only seven in the world. The sand appears pink because it is a mixture of white sand combined with red sand, formed from pieces of [[Foraminifera]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Komodo (island)}}\n* [[List of islands of Indonesia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{New7Wonders of Nature}}\n{{Tourist attractions in Indonesia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komodo (Island)}}\n\n[[Category:Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n[[Category:Inner Banda Arc]]\n[[Category:Komodo National Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n|name = Komodo <br /> <small>[[New 7 Wonders of Nature]]</small>\n|image_name = Komodo Island north aerial.jpg\n|image_caption = Northern tip of the island\n|map_image = ID - Komodo.PNG\n|map_caption = \n|native_name = \n|native_name_link = \n|location = [[Southeast Asia]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|8.55|S|119.45|E|region:ID_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n|archipelago = [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n|total_islands = \n|major_islands = \n|area_km2 = 390\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m = \n|country = Indonesia\n|country_admin_divisions_title = Province\n|country_admin_divisions = [[East Nusa Tenggara]]\n|population = c. 2000\n|population_as_of = \n|density_km2 = \n|ethnic_groups = [[Bugis]], others\n}}\n\n'''Komodo''' ({{lang-id|Pulau Komodo}}) is one of the 17,508 [[Islands of Indonesia|islands]] that comprise the [[Indonesia|Republic of Indonesia]]. The island is particularly notable as the habitat of the [[Komodo dragon]], the largest lizard on Earth, which is named after the island. Komodo Island has a surface area of 390 square kilometres and a human population of over two thousand. The people of the island are descendants of former [[convict|convicts]] who were exiled to the island and who have mixed with [[Bugis]] from [[Sulawesi]]. The people are primarily adherents of [[Islam in Indonesia|Islam]] but there are also [[Christianity in Indonesia|Christian]] and [[Hinduism in Indonesia|Hindu]] congregations.\n\nKomodo is part of the [[Lesser Sunda Islands|Lesser Sunda chain]] of islands and forms part of the [[Komodo National Park]]. In addition, the island is a popular destination for [[Scuba diving|diving]]. Administratively, it is part of the [[East Nusa Tenggara]] [[Provinces of Indonesia|Province]].\n\n==Description==\nKomodo is part of the [[Lesser Sunda Islands|Lesser Sunda chain]] of islands and forms part of the [[Komodo National Park]]. It lies between the substantially larger neighboring islands [[Sumbawa]] to the west and [[Flores]] to the east. The island's surface area covers 390 square kilometres.  Komodo Island is home to the Komodo Dragon, the largest lizard on earth.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest stories (among Westerners) of a dragon-like animal existing in the region circulated widely and attracted considerable attention.  But no Westerner visited the island to check the story until official interest was sparked in the early 1910s by stories from [[Dutch people|Dutch]] sailors based in [[Flores]] in [[East Nusa Tenggara]] about a mysterious creature. The creature was allegedly a dragon which inhabited a small island in the Lesser Sunda Islands (the main island of which is Flores).\n[[Image:Vegetation on Komodo Island.jpg|thumb|right|Vegetation on Komodo Island]]\n\nThe Dutch sailors reported that the creature measured up to seven metres (twenty-three feet) in length with a large body and mouth which constantly breathed fire. It burnt them and so they could not continue the investigation. It was believed then that the odd creature could fly. Hearing the reports, Lieutenant Steyn van Hensbroek, an official of the Dutch Colonial Administration in Flores, planned a trip to Komodo Island to continue the search himself. He armed himself, and accompanied by a team of soldiers, he landed on the island. After a few days, Hensbroek managed to kill one of the lizards to investigate.\n\nVan Hensbroek took the dragon to headquarters where measurements were taken. It was approximately 2.1 metres (6.9 feet) long, with a shape very similar to that of a [[lizard]]. More samples were then photographed by Peter A. Ouwens, the Director of the Zoological Museum and [[Bogor Botanical Gardens|Botanical Gardens]] in [[Bogor]], [[Java]]. The records that Ouwens made are the first reliable documentation of details about what is now called the Komodo dragon (or Komodo monitor).\n\nOuwens was keen to obtain additional samples. He recruited hunters who killed two dragons measuring 3.1 metres and 3.35 metres as well as capturing two pups, each measuring less than one metre. Ouwens carried out studies on the samples and concluded that the Komodo dragon was not a flame-thrower but was a type of [[monitor lizard]]. Research results were published in 1912. Ouwens named the giant lizard ''Varanus komodoensis''. Realizing the significance of the dragons on Komodo Island as an endangered species, the Dutch government issued a regulation on the protection of the lizards on Komodo Island in 1915.\n\nThe Komodo dragon became something of a living legend. In the decades since the Komodo was discovered, various scientific expeditions from a range of countries have carried out field research on the dragons on Komodo Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indonesiaindonesia.com/f/37477-sejarah-pulau-komodo/|title=Sejarah Pulau Komodo|work=indonesiaindonesia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Modern day==\nKomodo has a human population of over two thousand, spread out over the island and in the main [[Komodo (village)|Komodo village]]. The native population of Komodo, the [[Komodo people]], has been extinct since the 1980s.<ref>[http://sains.kompas.com/read/2013/01/28/15514880/penduduk.hidup.bersama.komodo Penduduk Hidup Bersama Komodo]</ref> The present day people of the island are descendants of former [[convicts]] who were exiled to Komodo and who have mixed with [[Bugis]] from [[Sulawesi]]. The population is primarily adherents of [[Islam in Indonesia|Islam]] but there are also [[Christianity in Indonesia|Christian]] and [[Hinduism in Indonesia|Hindu]] congregations. Administratively, it is part of the [[East Nusa Tenggara]] [[Provinces of Indonesia|province]]. The island is also a popular destination for [[Scuba diving|diving]] and it has been included into the controversial [[New7Wonders of Nature]] list since November 11, 2011.\n\n'''Temporary closure of Komodo Island'''\n\nIn April 2019, Indonesian authorities announced a plan to close Komodo Island to tourism for a limited period to allow for conservation efforts amid concerns over animal-smuggling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/04/tourists-banned-from-home-of-komodo-dragon-as-smugglers-eye-dwindling-numbers|title=Komodo considers tourist ban to help boost dragon numbers|publisher=The Guardian|date=4 April 2019}}</ref>  In July 2019, it was confirmed that the island would be closed as from the beginning of 2020. The Governor of Nusa Tenggara Timur province, Viktor B. Laiskodat, said that a budget of Rp 100 billion (around $US 7.2 million) would be provided to support the conservation program.<ref>'[https://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2019/07/18/komodo-island-to-be-closed-in-2020-agency.html?src=mostviewed&pg=/ Komodo Island to be closed in 2020: Agency'], ''The Jakarta Post'', 18 July 2019.</ref> The plan is controversial: Governor Laiskodat has suggested that an expensive entrance fee be charged to foreign tourists while local villagers who live on Komodo Island are worried about the possible loss of income.<ref>Rebecca Henscheke and Callistasia Wijaya, '[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/extra/5bBE5791M9/The_fight_for_Dragon_Island The fight for Dragon Island'], ''BBC World'', 25 July 2019.</ref> \n\n===Fauna===\n[[Image:Kdki.jpg|thumb|right|Komodo dragon]]\n\nThe [[Komodo dragon]], the world's largest living lizard, takes its name from the island. A type of [[monitor lizard]], it inhabits Komodo Island and some of the smaller surrounding islands, as well as part of western Flores. [[Javan rusa|Javan deer]] also inhabit the island, though they are not native. Other animals include [[water buffalo]], [[banded pig]]s, civets, cockatoo and macaques.\n\n===Pink beach===\nKomodo contains a beach with \"[[pink]]\" [[sand]], one of only seven in the world. The sand appears pink because it is a mixture of white sand combined with red sand, formed from pieces of [[Foraminifera]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Komodo (island)}}\n* [[List of islands of Indonesia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{New7Wonders of Nature}}\n{{Tourist attractions in Indonesia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komodo (Island)}}\n\n[[Category:Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n[[Category:Inner Banda Arc]]\n[[Category:Komodo National Park]]\n", "name_user": "Xindeho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Komodo_(island)"}
{"title_page": "Belle Gibson", "text_new": "{{Short description|Cancer fraudster}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Belle Gibson\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 160px\n| alt           = Profile photo of Sabontu in head-scarf\n| caption       = Belle Gibson, Jan 2020\n| birth_name    = Annabelle Natalie Gibson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth-date and age|October 8, 1991}}<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]], [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| home_town     = [[Northcote, Victoria|Northcote]], [[Victoria (state)|Victoria]], Australia\n| nationality   = [[Australian people|Australian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Fabricated claims of having had multiple cancers which were self-treated through diet and alternative medicine.  Fabricated claims of undergoing multiple heart surgeries and suffering strokes.  Fraudulent claims that $300,000 of income from sales had been donated to charities.\n| partner       = Clive Rothwell\n| children      = 1\n}}\n\n'''Annabelle Natalie''' \"'''Belle'''\" '''Gibson''' (born October 8, 1991<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\">{{cite web|last1=Staff (B & T Magazine)|title='We Checked Belle\u2019s Birth Certificate' Women\u2019s Weekly Editor Helen McCabe Tells B&T|url=http://www.bandt.com.au/media/we-checked-belle-gibsons-birth-certificate-australian-womens-weekly-editor-helen-mccabe|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=June 30, 2015|quote=the magazine [Women's Wear Daily] has seen a birth certificate provided by her mother, Natalie, which clearly states she was born on October 8, 1991,}}</ref> in [[Launceston, Tasmania|Laucneston]], [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]]) is a convicted [[Australian]] [[scammer]] and [[pseudoscience]] advocate. She is the author of ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] and its later companion cookbook. Throughout her career as a wellness guru, Gibson claimed she had a diagnosis involving multiple [[cancer]] pathologies throughout her internal organs; claimed she had forgone modern science-based medical treatments; claimed she was effectively self-managing her multiple cancers through diet, exercise, and [[alternative medicine|alternative therapies]]; and claimed to have donated significant proportions of her income and her company's profits to numerous charities.\n\nIn March 2015, after reports identified Gibson's [[fraud]]ulent claims regarding her charitable giving, further media investigation revealed that she had also fabricated her stories of cancer, and had lied about her age, personal life and history. Concerns were expressed that Gibson had led a profligate lifestyle, renting an upmarket town house, leasing a luxury car and office space, undergoing cosmetic dental procedures, purchasing designer clothes and holidaying internationally, on money claimed to have been raised for charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|title=Supporters turn on Belle Gibson as cancer claims unravel|last=Toscano|first=Nick|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|date=2015-03-14|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224720/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> With a collapsing [[social media]] support base, Gibson admitted in an April 2015 interview that her claims of having multiple cancers had been fabricated, stating that \"none of it's true\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/diet-and-fitness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|title=The Whole Pantry author Belle Gibson admits she lied about having terminal cancer|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=22 April 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224738/https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/health-and-wellness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|author2=Toscano, Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nGibson's actions were described as \"particularly predatory\"<ref name=\"sickness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|title=M\u00fcnchausen by internet: the sickness bloggers who fake it online|last1=Montague|first1=Jules|date=30 April 2015|work=The Guardian Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922173756/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|archive-date=2018-09-22|publisher=Guardian News & Media Ltd}}</ref> and \"deceit on a grand scale, for personal profit\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tuohy|first1=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson: a story of deceit, betrayal of trust on a grand scale|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/belle-gibson-a-story-of-deceit-betrayal-of-trust-on-a-grand-scale/story-fni0fhk1-1227315495119|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> On May 6, 2016, [[Consumer Affairs Victoria]] announced legal action against Gibson and Inkerman Road Nominees Pty Ltd (originally known as Belle Gibson Pty Ltd) for \"false claims by Ms. Gibson and her company concerning her diagnosis with terminal [[brain cancer]], her rejection of conventional cancer treatments in favour of natural remedies, and the donation of proceeds to various charities.\"<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\">{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson to face legal action over claims, Penguin agrees to enforceable undertaking - Media release|url=https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|publisher=Consumer Affairs Victoria|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=6 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602184610/https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 15 March 2017, the [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]] supported most of those claims, concluding that, \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer.\"<ref name=\"judgement\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nAccording to interviews she has given, Belle Gibson left her [[Brisbane]] family home at age 12 to live with a classmate, and later lived with a family friend.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Whole Pantry founder inspires in the face of terminal cancer|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/the-whole-pantry-founder-inspires-in-the-face-of-terminal-cancer/story-fniym874-1227133426731|website=News.com.au|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=28 November 2014}}</ref> Gibson attended [[Wynnum State High School]] in [[Manly, Queensland|Manly]], [[Queensland]], until dropping out in Year 10,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/wellness-guru-belle-gibson-opposed-vaccination-backed-medical-cannabis/story-fnihsrf2-1227260568033 | title=Wellness guru Belle Gibson 'opposed vaccination, backed medical cannabis' | work=The Courier Mail | date=13 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> although she also later claimed to have been [[homeschool]]ed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|title='Cancer survivor' Belle Gibson retains lawyer|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=March 12, 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223345/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> She worked for some time as a trainee for catering supply company PFD Food Services in [[Lytton, Queensland|Lytton]],<ref name = \"Psychopath\">{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-described-herself-as-a-distinguished-psychopath/story-fni0fiyv-1227259174931 | title=Mega blogger Belle Gibson described herself as a 'distinguished psychopath' | work=The Courier Mail | date=12 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> but [[social media]] reflected that by late 2008 she had relocated to [[Perth]], [[Western Australia]]. There, she was involved in the skateboarding culture and actively participated in its online community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=60945&p=2&archive=1|title=santa clause  Page 2|work=skateboard.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Back In Hospital - Round Three|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=65113&archive=0&blog=0&p=1|website=skateboard.com.au|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref> Gibson subsequently moved from Perth to [[Melbourne]] in July 2009 and became a mother one year later, at age 18. Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] in August 2013, at age 21.\n\nGibson reportedly told a prospective business partner in 2014 that she had \"[[Pseudonym|several names]]\" that she went under,<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|title=Friends and doctors raise doubts over 'Healing Belle' cancer claims|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=March 10, 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-220355/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> and in her most recent interview with ''[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]'' claimed \"her mother changed her name five times\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Clair|title=What it's really like to interview Belle Gibson|url=http://www.aww.com.au/latest-news/in-the-mag/what-its-like-to-interview-belle-gibson-20282|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Australian Women's Weekly|publisher=Baeur Media}}</ref> Gibson's corporate filings indicate that she is three years younger than she publicly claims to be.<ref name=\"The Australian\"/>\n\n===''The Whole Pantry''===\nAfter Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' app, it was reportedly downloaded 200,000 times within its first month. Gibson soon after signed a book deal with [[Lantern Books]], an imprint of [[Penguin Books]], for an accompanying table top [[cookbook]], which was published in October 2014. She further worked with [[Apple Inc.]] in September 2014 to transition the app as a privileged pre-installed default third party inclusion in the [[Apple Watch]]'s April 2015 launch.<ref name=\"auto\"/> By early 2015, it was estimated that in excess of $1 million had been made in sales of ''The Whole Pantry'' app and book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|title=Belle Gibson - The Whole Pantry|work=Elle}}</ref> Gibson chronicled her battle with [[cancer]] on a blog of the same name, but \"doubts about her claims surfaced after she failed to deliver a promised $300,000 donation to a charity\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mendham|first1=Tim|date=June 2015|title=Not Healthy|url=https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|journal=The Skeptic|publisher=[[Australian Skeptics]]|volume=35|issue=2|page=9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226053715/https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-26}}</ref>\n\nBefore doubts were raised about her health and charitable donation claims, Gibson had intended to expand her brand beyond the app, having earlier registered the [[Internet domain|domain]] ''The Whole Life'', and advertised in December 2014 to recruit an IT specialist to expand the app and brand portfolio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|title=Remote Design Job - UI / UX Designer @ The Whole Pantry - WFH.io|work=wfh.io|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420174840/https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Both ''The Whole Pantry'' app and ''The Whole Life'' were registered by Gibson's partner, Clive Rothwell, in her corporate name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholelife|title=Thewholelife.com Whois Lookup - Who.is - Who.is|work=who.is}}</ref>  The Whole Pantry registrar was amended in March 2015 after the controversy broke.<ref>{{cite web|title=TheWholePantryApp.Com|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholepantryapp|website=Who.Is|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''The Whole Pantry'' has unequivocally denied that Gibson ever helped anyone to reject conventional cancer treatment, Gibson has been quoted from her social media posts as claiming that she had \"countless times helped others\" to forgo conventional medical treatment for cancer and to treat themselves \"naturally\", as well as \"leading them down natural therapy for everything from fertility, depression, bone damage and other types of cancer\".<ref name=\"theage-backlash\" />\n\n===Health claims===\nIn interviews, Gibson claimed to have suffered from malignant brain, [[leukemia|blood]], [[splenic tumor|spleen]], [[endometrial cancer|uterine]], [[liver cancer|liver]], and [[kidney cancer|kidney]] cancers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/news/the-whole-pantry-withdrawn-holistic-recipe-book-taken-off-shelves-as-authors-cancer-claims-are-disputed-10114642.html|title=The Whole Pantry withdrawn: Holistic recipe book taken off shelves as Belle Gibson's cancer claims are disputed|work=The Independent}}</ref> which she attributed to a reaction to the [[Gardasil]] cervical cancer vaccine.<ref name = \"Psychopath\"/> When the book was launched in November 2014, Gibson claimed in its preface that she had been \"stable for two years now with no growth of the cancer\",<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\"/> but her story soon emerged as inconsistent: she also told media outlets that the cancer had reached her liver and kidneys, and three months earlier had posted on ''The Whole Pantry'''s [[Facebook]] page that her cancer had spread to her brain, blood, spleen, and uterus. She previously claimed that she had undergone [[heart surgery]] several times and to have momentarily died on the operating table. Gibson also claimed to have suffered a [[stroke]]. However, she was unable to substantiate her medical claims nor name the doctors who diagnosed and treated her. She also did not bear any surgical scars from her heart operations.<ref name=\"The Australian\" />\n\nGibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s statements regarding the benefits of exercise, healthy eating and a positive mindset were uncontroversial, being widely acknowledged as conducive to holistic well being. However, on her now-deleted [[Instagram]] account and in other social media, Gibson also promoted more controversial or potentially dangerous alternative medical practices, including [[Gerson therapy]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debelle|first1=Penelope|last2=Hadfield|first2=Shelley|title=Belle Gibson and The Whole Pantry: Is her story fact or fiction?|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-and-the-whole-pantry-is-her-story-fact-or-fiction/story-fni0dguy-1227265261138|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=The Advertiser|publisher=News Corp}}</ref> [[anti-vaccination]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Piotrowski|first1=Daniel|last2=Noble|first2=Freya|title='She pushed me not to vaccinate my kids'|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2990598/She-tried-convince-not-vaccinate-kids-Belle-Gibson-s-betrayed-former-friend-says-Pantry-founder-come-clean-truth-cancer-survival-story.html|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=Daily Mail Australia|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd}}</ref> and the consumption of non-pasteurised [[raw milk]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Andrew|last2=Cavanagh|first2=Rebekah|title=Lifestyle blogger Belle Gibson slips up on booze, milk|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/lifestyle-blogger-belle-gibson-slips-up-on-booze-milk/|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\nThe highly controversial Gerson therapy had been similarly promoted by another Australian wellness blogger, [[Jessica Ainscough]], whose funeral Gibson attended when Ainscough succumbed to cancer in late February 2015. With approximately 97% of the Australian population under seven years of age immunised, Federal [[vaccination policy]] heavily penalises parents who refuse to vaccinate their children, by denying access to significant welfare and other benefits, worth approximately $11,700 per annum. The sale of raw milk for human consumption is illegal in Australia and, in [[Victoria (state)|Victoria]], one three-year-old died and another four children under the age of five became seriously ill after consuming non-pasteurised milk in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Milman|first1=Oliver|title=Victoria launches crackdown on sale of 'raw' unpasteurised milk|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/dec/28/victoria-launches-crackdown-on-sale-of-raw-unpasteurised-milk|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable claims===\nAs Gibson's medical claims were being scrutinised, allegations emerged that charitable contributions raised in 2013 and 2014 had not been given to their intended causes.<ref name=\"theage-backlash\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|title=Backlash over app developer Belle Gibson's missing charity money|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=9 March 2015|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213648/https://www.theage.com.au/technology/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Australia|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=\"essentialbaby\">{{cite news | url=http://www.essentialbaby.com.au/life-style/current-affairs/belle-gibson-the-missing-charity-money-and-the-confounding-cancer-claims-20150310-13zsel.html | title=Belle Gibson, the missing charity money and the confounding cancer claims | work=Essential Baby | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Gibson denied the charges,<ref name=\"newscomau-refutes\">{{cite news | url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-the-whole-pantry-refutes-claims-about-charity-donations/story-fniym3t1-1227255183760 | title=Belle Gibson's The Whole Pantry refutes claims about charity donations | work=news.com.au | date=10 March 2015 | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> but [[Fairfax Media]] revealed that she had \"failed to hand over proceeds solicited in the name of five charities\" and had \"grossly overstated the company's total donations to different causes\".<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\" /> Two charities confirmed to ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper that Gibson's company had used their names in fundraising drives but had either failed to deliver the donations or had inadequately accounted for the funds.<ref name=\"erased\"/>\n\nGibson had claimed on a number of occasions in 2014 that ''The Whole Pantry'' had donated approximately $300,000 to charities, including maternal healthcare in developing nations, medical support for children with cancer, and funding schools in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/macman/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140723-ztvos.html|title=Pop into The Pantry app for a healthier lifestyle|last=Barker|first=Garry|date=July 17, 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213102/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140717-ztvos.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In late 2014, when ''The Whole Pantry'' app was pre-installed on the Apple [[iPad]], Gibson claimed through her Instagram account to be working with twenty different charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson // thewholepantry@healing_belle|url=https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|website=Populagram|publisher=Populgram, Instagram|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422174823/https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|archive-date=22 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gibson has long claimed in her [[LinkedIn]] professional networking profile, established in February 2013, to be a [[philanthropist]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson, The Whole Pantry|url=https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=30 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430210329/https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|archive-date=30 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGibson eventually admitted, in relation to fraud proceedings, that she had seriously overstated the level of charitable contributions that had been made. Subsequent media reports in March 2015 revealed that it could only be ascertained that an estimated $7,000 of the previously claimed $300,000 had been donated to a total of three charities, with at least $1,000 of the $7,000 reportedly having been donated only after Gibson became aware of the Fairfax investigation into her earlier claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150308-13xgqk.html|title=Charity money promised by 'inspirational' health app developer Belle Gibson not handed over|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|last2=Toscano|first2=NIck|date=8 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-211226/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150306-13xgqk.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Another $1,000 of the $7,000 had been donated to a charitable cause under Rothwell's name, rather than Gibson's or the company name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|title=Supporters - The ASRC Food Justice Truck - StartSomeGood: Igniting Ideas, Investment & Impact.|work=StartSomeGood|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420193743/http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2015, the parents of a young child suffering from brain cancer, whom Gibson had befriended, came forward to report that they had been unaware that Gibson had earlier been claiming to be fundraising for their child's treatment on their behalf. The family had never received any funds from her or ''The Whole Pantry'', and suspected Gibson had been using information gleaned from the family's experiences to underpin her own claims to having brain cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|title=Family of desperately ill boy fear health guru Belle Gibson used their son to bolster her cancer claims|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/family-of-desperately-ill-boy-fear-health-guru-belle-gibson-used-their-son-to-bolster-her-cancer-claims/story-fni0fit3-1227273020233|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|publisher=[[Herald Sun]], [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Concern over publisher culpability===\nAs the controversy grew, questions began to be raised about Apple, Penguin and the Australian media's lack of due diligence in ''[[prima facie]]'' accepting Gibson's claims to suffering multiple cancers, an issue taken up by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]'s ''[[Media Watch (TV program)|Media Watch]]'' program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barry|first1=Paul|title=How the media fell for Belle|url=http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s4198886.htm|website=ABC.NET.AU|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nApple Inc., in response to media enquiry in March 2015, declined to remove ''The Whole Pantry'' app from sale, stating that it was only concerned about the functionality of the app. However, ''The Whole Pantry'' was soon thereafter removed from inclusion in the Apple Watch launch. Apple subsequently deleted the app from the Apple Store, and removed it from all Apple Watch promotional material. Apple has not provided any public comment regarding the reasons behind the removal of the app,<ref>{{cite news|last=Riley|first=Duncan|title=Fake cancer survivor Belle Gibson's app pulled from App Store, still linked to Apple Watch though|url=http://siliconangle.com/blog/2015/03/17/fake-cancer-survivor-belle-gibsons-app-pulled-from-app-store-still-linked-to-apple-watch-though/|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Siliconangle.com|publisher=SiliconANGLE Media|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> but an internal email from an Australian executive to the company's US office acknowledged that the removal would be subject to comment.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nLantern Books, when initially approached by investigative journalists, claimed it had not confirmed the validity of Gibson's cancer claims as it was not required for a cookbook.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hallbaeck|first1=Jan|title=The 'hole' in the pantry story: should Penguin have validated Belle Gibson's cancer claims?|url=https://theconversation.com/the-hole-in-the-pantry-story-should-penguin-have-validated-belle-gibsons-cancer-claims-38843|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=The Conversation|publisher=The Conversation Trust|date=16 March 2015}}</ref> Soon after, as the controversy grew, Penguin withdrew the book from sale, citing a lack of response from Gibson to its queries relating to the media accusations. However, Fairfax reported that Penguin had, prior to publication of the book, already quizzed and videotaped Gibson on her cancer story, as recounted in the [[preface]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|title=Publisher Penguin pulls Belle Gibson cook book The Whole Pantry|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=16 March 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2015.05.01-005533/http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|archive-date=2015-05-01|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> Penguin agreed to pay A$30,000 to the [[Consumer Affairs Victoria|Victorian Consumer Law Fund]] as a penalty for failing to validate the factual content of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|title=Cancer-faking blogger faces legal action|date=2016-05-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''[[Elle magazine|Elle Australia]]'' magazine, published by [[Bauer Media Group]], admitted that following a laudatory December 2014 story on Gibson, they had received but ultimately dismissed anonymous claims that she was fabricating her story.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawrence|first1=Vanessa|title=What we know about Belle Gibson|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Elle Australia|publisher=Elle Australia}}</ref> A second Bauer magazine, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', which had awarded Gibson its 2014 \"Fun Fearless Female\" social media award, admitted that it too had received and dismissed a similar email.<ref name=\"honest\" /> After Gibson's confessions, the magazine decided not to strip her of the award, stating that she had been \"reader nominated and reader voted.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharp|first1=Annette|title=Cosmo defend failure to research Belle cancer claims and says she can keep Fun Fearless Female award|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/cosmo-defend-failure-to-research-belle-cancer-claims-and-says-she-can-keep-fun-fearless-female-award/story-fni0cvc9-1227318967969|accessdate=25 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=NewsCorp|date=24 April 2015}}</ref> However, a month earlier, ''Cosmopolitan''{{'}}s associate editor stated that they \"put forward the nomination myself\", indicating that the magazine {{ndash}} not the public {{ndash}} had been instrumental in promoting Gibson's award.<ref name=\"honest\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|title=An honest account of our experience with Belle Gibson|last1=Sams|first1=Lauren|date=17 March 2015|work=Cosmopolitan Australia|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091405/http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|archive-date=18 May 2015|publisher=Bauer Media Group}}</ref>\n\nA conventional cancer research professional from the [[Garvan Institute of Medical Research]] also went public to state that, by failing to conduct basic [[fact checking]] and providing \"unfiltered [[public relations|PR]]\" to Gibson's untested claims, an uncritical media had been complicit in her \"scam\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burke|first1=Liz|title='They are all complicit': Cancer researcher Dr Darren Saunders slams Belle Gibson's 'enablers'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/they-are-all-complicit-cancer-researcher-dr-darren-saunders-slams-belle-gibsons-enablers/story-fneuzlbd-1227317296471|accessdate=23 April 2015|agency=News.com.au|publisher=News Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Erasing the story===\nOnce the controversy surfaced in the media, ''The Whole Pantry'' began removing any comments made on its (since deleted) Facebook page that questioned Gibson's claims, asserting that these comments only added to \"the misinformation\" of the initial Fairfax article. This selective deletion drew even more negative comment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Jenni|title=The mystery of Belle Gibson, who claimed she cured cancer with clean living|url=http://mashable.com/2015/03/29/belle-gibson-whole-pantry/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Mashable Australia|publisher=Mashable Inc.}}</ref>\n\nSimultaneously, posts that Gibson had made on her Instagram account that made reference to her cancers or charitable donations were also selectively deleted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Does Belle Gibson Actually Have Cancer?|url=http://realitybasedmedicine.blogspot.com.au/2015/03/does-belle-gibson-actually-have-cancer.html|website=Reality Based Medicine|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> Soon after, all posts were deleted from Gibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s Instagram accounts. Around the same time, individual postings about Gibson's cancer, and claims of having died briefly while under heart surgery, were also being selectively deleted by the administrator of her blog \"at the request of a user\".<ref name=\"erased\">{{cite news|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|title=Whole Pantry founder Belle Gibson's stories of beating terminal cancer erased from internet|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/whole-pantry-founder-belle-gibsons-stories-of-beating-terminal-cancer-erased-from-internet/story-fni0fit3-1227257742137|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> Accounts across a number of social media platforms were soon either abandoned, made private, or deleted in their entirety.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Michael|first1=Sarah|last2=Dean|first2=Sarah|title=Belle Gibson's partying past reveals a love of beer, cask wine and donuts... and it's a long way from the organic regime she claims cured her 'terminal' brain cancer|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2997754/Blogger-Belle-Gibson-s-book-cancelled-U-S-wellness-empire-continues-collapse-allegations-faked-terminal-cancer.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Daily Mail Australia|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd}}</ref>\n\nGibson subsequently established another Facebook account under the alias Harry Gibson, which was made private and used to hit back at Facebook followers questioning her claims or speaking to the media.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|last2=Tuohy|first2=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson slams 'fake cancer' claims in online rant|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/health-blogger-and-app-developer-belle-gibson-hits-back-at-bullying-critics-20150315-144g0v.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\n===Admission of deceit===\nIn late April 2015, Gibson gave an interview to ''The Australian Women's Weekly'', in which she admitted to having fabricated all her cancer claims. Gibson attributed her deceit to her upbringing, and specifically to [[child neglect|neglect]] by her now-[[Family estrangement|estranged]] mother, claiming to having been forced to take care of herself and her brother since the age of 5.<ref name=\"news.com.au\">{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Rebecca|title=Belle Gibson: 'No, None of it is true'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-no-none-of-it-is-true/story-fniym874-1227315232565|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> The interview was, however, described as an admission of deceit, without expression of regret or apology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Matt|title=Nothing to like about this pretty little liar|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/nothing-to-like-about-this-pretty-little-liar/story-fni0ffsx-1227320920457|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp Ltd|date=25 April 2015}}</ref> In a May 2015 interview with the same magazine, Gibson's mother Natalie Dal-Bello refuted several claims Gibson had made about her family, including the false claim that her brother was [[autism|autistic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson's mum slams troubled childhood claims as 'a lot of rubbish'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-mum-slams-troubled-childhood-claims-as-a-lot-of-rubbish/story-fneuz9ev-1227358455303|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> Gibson's ''Women's Weekly'' interview was arranged by [[Bespoke Approach]], and Gibson was provided ''[[pro bono]]'' representation by the company during the interview.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/strewth/toil-for-the-belle/news-story/5be985d1f1b73c1a0fda7dab453ffab1|title=Toil for the Belle|last1=Jeffrey|first1=James|date=23 April 2015|work=The Australian|accessdate=25 April 2015|url-status=live|publisher=NewsCorp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Gibson was rumoured to have received A$45,000 for an interview with [[Nine Network]]'s ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|title=Belle Gibson promises to tell the whole truth: \u2018I have lost everything\u2019|last=Willis|first=Charlotte|date=2015-06-25|website=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Corp Australia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003193353/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|archive-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/broadcast/nine-network-faces-backlash-over-60-minutes-interview-with-belle-gibson/news-story/311065149cfe5289ea2b4d3af6ef283d|title=Nine Network faces backlash over 60 Minutes interview with Belle Gibson|last=Guilliatt|first=Richard|date=25 Jun 2015|work=The Australian|publisher=News Corp|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-date=|access-date=24 Jun 2017}}</ref> Stefanie Spinks of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' wrote that \"by accepting $45,000 for her interview, Belle is sending the message that people can profit off stealing, lying and taking advantage of people's good intentions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3138530/This-absolute-disgrace-Thousands-former-Belle-Gibson-supporters-sign-online-petition-demanding-cancer-fraud-donate-fee-upcoming-interview-charity.html|title=Thousands of former Belle Gibson supporters sign online petition demanding the cancer fraud donate any fee from upcoming interview to charity|work=Daily Mail|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> During this interview, Gibson claimed to have been visited at home by a doctor named Mark Johns who had a portable, German-made electronic machine with paddles and lights that diagnosed her cancers. She also claimed that she believed she was taking [[oral chemotherapy]] prescribed by this same doctor. No one has found any trace of this person nor any information on the machine that was used to make a diagnosis.\n\n===Legal action===\n\nConsumer Affairs Victoria brought legal action against Gibson for allegedly breaking Australian consumer law. The regulator said it had conducted an in-depth investigation of Gibson's activities and applied to Australia's Federal Court for leave to pursue legal action. Gibson's publisher, Penguin Australia, has already agreed to pay A$30,000 (US$22,200; \u00a315,300) to the Victorian Consumer Law Fund as a penalty for releasing The Whole Pantry, which was not fact checked.<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson: Australian blogger who faked cancer faces legal action|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2017, Federal Court Justice [[Debra Mortimer]] delivered the decision that \"most but not all\" of the claims were proven. Gibson did not appear in court for the decision. Justice Mortimer found that Gibson's claims had been misleading and deceptive, and that \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer from the time she began making these claims in public to promote ''The Whole Pantry Book'' and the apps in mid-2013\", but there was not enough evidence to prove that she was not acting out of delusion.<ref name=\"judgement\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2017/03/15/06/22/belle-gibsons-judgement-to-be-handed-down-in-court|title=Disgraced wellness blogger Belle Gibson facing more than $1 million in fines|date=15 March 2017|work=9 News|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 FCA 240\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|240|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson |date=15 March 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref name=\"fad\"/>\n\nIn September 2017, Gibson was fined A$410,000 (US$310,000; \u00a3240,000) for making false claims about her donations to charity.<ref name=\"2017 FCA 1148\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|1148|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson (No 3) |date=28 September 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Karen |last=Percy |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-28/disgraced-wellness-blogger-belle-gibson-fined/8995500 |title=Fake wellness blogger Belle Gibson fined over cancer claims |date=28 September 2017 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission}}</ref> {{As of|2019|04}}, Gibson had not yet paid the fine, and authorities were seeking power to charge her with [[contempt of court]]. A new trial was set for 14 May  and she faced an undetermined number of years in jail if she did not attend.<ref>{{cite news |title=Belle Gibson faces jail time if $410k fine for cancer fraud goes unpaid |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-27/belle-gibson-faces-jail-term-for-unpaid-cancer-fraud-fine/10558150 |date=28 November 2018 |access-date=28 November 2018 |last=Oaten |first=James |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson to explain why she hasn\u2019t paid $410k fine for duping sick Aussies|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/belle-gibson-to-explain-why-she-hasnt-paid-410k-fine-for-duping-sick-aussies/news-story/43c24e05cb91d5b6f74f3aa2e26b392c|date=17 April 2019|access-date=18 April 2019|publisher=news.com.au}}</ref> As of mid-September 2019, Gibson still had not paid, claiming to be broke, and Consumer Affairs Victoria were still seeking to enforce the penalty.<ref>\"Belle Gibson 'in hiding'\". The Daily Telegraph (Australia), 15 Sep 2019, p. 11</ref> In a 2017 letter later released by the Federal Court, Gibson had stated that she was $170,000 in debt, and had $5,000 to her name.<ref name=\"letter\" />\n\n==House raid by police==\nOn 22 January 2020, the Sheriff\u2019s Office of Victoria  raided Gibson's home in Northcote and seized items to recoup Gibson's unpaid fines,<ref name=\"raided\"/> which, due to interest and costs, exceeded half a million dollars.<ref name=\"sheriff\"/>\n\n==Claimed adoption into Oromo community==\nOn 23 January 2020, a Shabo Media video from October 2019 surfaced in which Gibson was wearing a headscarf and speaking partially in [[Oromo language]] (referring to herself as \"Sanbotu\"), discussing the political situation in [[Ethiopia]] with an interviewer and referring to Ethiopia as \"back home\". She professed to have been adopted by the Ethiopian community in Melbourne after volunteering for four years, calling the adoption a gift from \"Allah\".<ref name=\"adopted\"/><ref name=\"community\"/>\n\nHowever, on the same day, the president of the Australian Oromo Community Association in Victoria, Tarekegn Chimdi, stated that Gibson was not a registered volunteer, \"is not a community member and she\u2019s also not working with the community,\" and that he had only seen her at events two or three times. He expressed that nobody seemed to know who she was and he had only just learnt of her backstory, and expressed a desire for her to stop saying she is part of the community.<ref name=\"rejected\"/><ref name=\"Melbourne\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ashley Kirilow]], a Canadian fraudster who raised money for cancer charities by falsely claiming that she had cancer\n*[[Michael Guglielmucci]], an Australian singer who claimed to have cancer to boost his performing career\n*[[Diet and cancer]]\n*[[Munchausen syndrome]] <ref name=\"sickness\"/><ref name=\"munchausen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"letter\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|title=2017 letter Belle Gibson wrote detailing debts released|date=2020-02-18|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050632/https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|archive-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"munchausen\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|title=Munchausen syndrome: Why bloggers like cancer fraud Belle Gibson fake sickness online|last=Nianias|first=Helen|date=2015-04-30|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent Digital News & Media Ltd|location=UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428224900/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|archive-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Melbourne\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|title=Belle Gibson has been adopted by Ethiopian community in Melbourne|last=Smith|first=Rohan|date=2020-01-24|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126195951/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"fad\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|title=Belle Gibson backs new health fad ahead of court judgment|last=Cavanagh|first=Rebekah|date=15 March 2017|work=Herald Sun|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-125528/https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"community\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|title=Belle Gibson 'adopted' by Ethiopian community|last=Kinsella|first=Elise|date=2020-01-23|work=ABC News|location=Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126203125/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|title=Apple exposed over Belle Gibson affair|last1=Toscano|first1=Nick|date=19 November 2017|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223125/https://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"The Australian\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/story-e6frg8zx-1227255933051|title=Mega-blogger Belle Gibson casts doubt on her own cancer claims|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|date=10 March 2015|newspaper=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/2017.01.26-011131/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/megablogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/news-story/de179f2f17de51d1071096eb7bd2bdee|archive-date=2017-01-26|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rejected\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|title=Cancer fraudster rejected by Ethiopians|last=Akerman|first=Tessa|date=24 January 2020|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-132450/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"adopted\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|title=Cancer fraudster Belle Gibson \u2018adopted\u2019 by Ethiopian community|date=January 23, 2020|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123132020/https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|archive-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sheriff\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|title=Sheriff raids cancer fraudster Belle Gibson's home over unpaid fine|last=AAP|date=2020-01-22|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122215711/https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|archive-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"raided\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|title=Belle Gibson\u2019s home raided by sheriff over cancer fraud fine|last=Urban|first=Rebecca|date=2020-01-22|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-210004/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150314032024/http://thewholepantryapp.com/ The Whole Pantry website], registered by Gibson\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Belle}}\n[[Category:Australian fraudsters]]\n[[Category:Health fraud]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:People from Launceston, Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Alternative cancer treatment advocates]]\n[[Category:Confidence tricksters]]\n[[Category:Medical controversies in Australia]]\n[[Category:People convicted for health fraud]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Cancer fraudster}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Belle Gibson\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 160px\n| alt           = Profile photo of Sabontu in head-scarf\n| caption       = Belle Gibson, Jan 2020\n| birth_name    = Annabelle Natalie Gibson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth-date and age|October 8, 1991}}<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[Launceston, Tasmania]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| home_town     = [[Northcote, Victoria]], Australia\n| nationality   = [[Australian people|Australian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Fabricated claims of having had multiple cancers which were self-treated through diet and alternative medicine.  Fabricated claims of undergoing multiple heart surgeries and suffering strokes.  Fraudulent claims that $300,000 of income from sales had been donated to charities.\n| partner       = Clive Rothwell\n| children      = 1\n}}\n\n'''Annabelle Natalie''' \"'''Belle'''\" '''Gibson''' (born October 8, 1991<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\">{{cite web|last1=Staff (B & T Magazine)|title='We Checked Belle\u2019s Birth Certificate' Women\u2019s Weekly Editor Helen McCabe Tells B&T|url=http://www.bandt.com.au/media/we-checked-belle-gibsons-birth-certificate-australian-womens-weekly-editor-helen-mccabe|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=June 30, 2015|quote=the magazine [Women's Wear Daily] has seen a birth certificate provided by her mother, Natalie, which clearly states she was born on October 8, 1991,}}</ref> in [[Launceston, Tasmania]], [[Australia]]) is a convicted [[Australian]] [[scammer]] and [[pseudoscience]] advocate. She is the author of ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] and its later companion cookbook. Throughout her career as a wellness guru, Gibson claimed she had a diagnosis involving multiple [[cancer]] pathologies throughout her internal organs; claimed she had forgone modern science-based medical treatments; claimed she was effectively self-managing her multiple cancers through diet, exercise, and [[alternative medicine|alternative therapies]]; and claimed to have donated significant proportions of her income and her company's profits to numerous charities.\n\nIn March 2015, after reports identified Gibson's [[fraud]]ulent claims regarding her charitable giving, further media investigation revealed that she had also fabricated her stories of cancer, and had lied about her age, personal life and history. Concerns were expressed that Gibson had led a profligate lifestyle, renting an upmarket town house, leasing a luxury car and office space, undergoing cosmetic dental procedures, purchasing designer clothes and holidaying internationally, on money claimed to have been raised for charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|title=Supporters turn on Belle Gibson as cancer claims unravel|last=Toscano|first=Nick|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|date=2015-03-14|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224720/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> With a collapsing [[social media]] support base, Gibson admitted in an April 2015 interview that her claims of having multiple cancers had been fabricated, stating that \"none of it's true\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/diet-and-fitness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|title=The Whole Pantry author Belle Gibson admits she lied about having terminal cancer|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=22 April 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224738/https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/health-and-wellness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|author2=Toscano, Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nGibson's actions were described as \"particularly predatory\"<ref name=\"sickness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|title=M\u00fcnchausen by internet: the sickness bloggers who fake it online|last1=Montague|first1=Jules|date=30 April 2015|work=The Guardian Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922173756/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|archive-date=2018-09-22|publisher=Guardian News & Media Ltd}}</ref> and \"deceit on a grand scale, for personal profit\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tuohy|first1=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson: a story of deceit, betrayal of trust on a grand scale|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/belle-gibson-a-story-of-deceit-betrayal-of-trust-on-a-grand-scale/story-fni0fhk1-1227315495119|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> On May 6, 2016, [[Consumer Affairs Victoria]] announced legal action against Gibson and Inkerman Road Nominees Pty Ltd (originally known as Belle Gibson Pty Ltd) for \"false claims by Ms. Gibson and her company concerning her diagnosis with terminal [[brain cancer]], her rejection of conventional cancer treatments in favour of natural remedies, and the donation of proceeds to various charities.\"<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\">{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson to face legal action over claims, Penguin agrees to enforceable undertaking - Media release|url=https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|publisher=Consumer Affairs Victoria|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=6 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602184610/https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 15 March 2017, the [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]] supported most of those claims, concluding that, \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer.\"<ref name=\"judgement\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nAccording to interviews she has given, Belle Gibson left her [[Brisbane]] family home at age 12 to live with a classmate, and later lived with a family friend.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Whole Pantry founder inspires in the face of terminal cancer|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/the-whole-pantry-founder-inspires-in-the-face-of-terminal-cancer/story-fniym874-1227133426731|website=News.com.au|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=28 November 2014}}</ref> Gibson attended [[Wynnum State High School]] in [[Manly, Queensland|Manly]], [[Queensland]], until dropping out in Year 10,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/wellness-guru-belle-gibson-opposed-vaccination-backed-medical-cannabis/story-fnihsrf2-1227260568033 | title=Wellness guru Belle Gibson 'opposed vaccination, backed medical cannabis' | work=The Courier Mail | date=13 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> although she also later claimed to have been [[homeschool]]ed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|title='Cancer survivor' Belle Gibson retains lawyer|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=March 12, 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223345/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> She worked for some time as a trainee for catering supply company PFD Food Services in [[Lytton, Queensland|Lytton]],<ref name = \"Psychopath\">{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-described-herself-as-a-distinguished-psychopath/story-fni0fiyv-1227259174931 | title=Mega blogger Belle Gibson described herself as a 'distinguished psychopath' | work=The Courier Mail | date=12 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> but [[social media]] reflected that by late 2008 she had relocated to [[Perth]], [[Western Australia]]. There, she was involved in the skateboarding culture and actively participated in its online community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=60945&p=2&archive=1|title=santa clause  Page 2|work=skateboard.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Back In Hospital - Round Three|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=65113&archive=0&blog=0&p=1|website=skateboard.com.au|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref> Gibson subsequently moved from Perth to [[Melbourne]] in July 2009 and became a mother one year later, at age 18. Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] in August 2013, at age 21.\n\nGibson reportedly told a prospective business partner in 2014 that she had \"[[Pseudonym|several names]]\" that she went under,<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|title=Friends and doctors raise doubts over 'Healing Belle' cancer claims|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=March 10, 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-220355/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> and in her most recent interview with ''[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]'' claimed \"her mother changed her name five times\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Clair|title=What it's really like to interview Belle Gibson|url=http://www.aww.com.au/latest-news/in-the-mag/what-its-like-to-interview-belle-gibson-20282|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Australian Women's Weekly|publisher=Baeur Media}}</ref> Gibson's corporate filings indicate that she is three years younger than she publicly claims to be.<ref name=\"The Australian\"/>\n\n===''The Whole Pantry''===\nAfter Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' app, it was reportedly downloaded 200,000 times within its first month. Gibson soon after signed a book deal with [[Lantern Books]], an imprint of [[Penguin Books]], for an accompanying table top [[cookbook]], which was published in October 2014. She further worked with [[Apple Inc.]] in September 2014 to transition the app as a privileged pre-installed default third party inclusion in the [[Apple Watch]]'s April 2015 launch.<ref name=\"auto\"/> By early 2015, it was estimated that in excess of $1 million had been made in sales of ''The Whole Pantry'' app and book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|title=Belle Gibson - The Whole Pantry|work=Elle}}</ref> Gibson chronicled her battle with [[cancer]] on a blog of the same name, but \"doubts about her claims surfaced after she failed to deliver a promised $300,000 donation to a charity\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mendham|first1=Tim|date=June 2015|title=Not Healthy|url=https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|journal=The Skeptic|publisher=[[Australian Skeptics]]|volume=35|issue=2|page=9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226053715/https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-26}}</ref>\n\nBefore doubts were raised about her health and charitable donation claims, Gibson had intended to expand her brand beyond the app, having earlier registered the [[Internet domain|domain]] ''The Whole Life'', and advertised in December 2014 to recruit an IT specialist to expand the app and brand portfolio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|title=Remote Design Job - UI / UX Designer @ The Whole Pantry - WFH.io|work=wfh.io|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420174840/https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Both ''The Whole Pantry'' app and ''The Whole Life'' were registered by Gibson's partner, Clive Rothwell, in her corporate name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholelife|title=Thewholelife.com Whois Lookup - Who.is - Who.is|work=who.is}}</ref>  The Whole Pantry registrar was amended in March 2015 after the controversy broke.<ref>{{cite web|title=TheWholePantryApp.Com|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholepantryapp|website=Who.Is|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''The Whole Pantry'' has unequivocally denied that Gibson ever helped anyone to reject conventional cancer treatment, Gibson has been quoted from her social media posts as claiming that she had \"countless times helped others\" to forgo conventional medical treatment for cancer and to treat themselves \"naturally\", as well as \"leading them down natural therapy for everything from fertility, depression, bone damage and other types of cancer\".<ref name=\"theage-backlash\" />\n\n===Health claims===\nIn interviews, Gibson claimed to have suffered from malignant brain, [[leukemia|blood]], [[splenic tumor|spleen]], [[endometrial cancer|uterine]], [[liver cancer|liver]], and [[kidney cancer|kidney]] cancers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/news/the-whole-pantry-withdrawn-holistic-recipe-book-taken-off-shelves-as-authors-cancer-claims-are-disputed-10114642.html|title=The Whole Pantry withdrawn: Holistic recipe book taken off shelves as Belle Gibson's cancer claims are disputed|work=The Independent}}</ref> which she attributed to a reaction to the [[Gardasil]] cervical cancer vaccine.<ref name = \"Psychopath\"/> When the book was launched in November 2014, Gibson claimed in its preface that she had been \"stable for two years now with no growth of the cancer\",<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\"/> but her story soon emerged as inconsistent: she also told media outlets that the cancer had reached her liver and kidneys, and three months earlier had posted on ''The Whole Pantry'''s [[Facebook]] page that her cancer had spread to her brain, blood, spleen, and uterus. She previously claimed that she had undergone [[heart surgery]] several times and to have momentarily died on the operating table. Gibson also claimed to have suffered a [[stroke]]. However, she was unable to substantiate her medical claims nor name the doctors who diagnosed and treated her. She also did not bear any surgical scars from her heart operations.<ref name=\"The Australian\" />\n\nGibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s statements regarding the benefits of exercise, healthy eating and a positive mindset were uncontroversial, being widely acknowledged as conducive to holistic well being. However, on her now-deleted [[Instagram]] account and in other social media, Gibson also promoted more controversial or potentially dangerous alternative medical practices, including [[Gerson therapy]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debelle|first1=Penelope|last2=Hadfield|first2=Shelley|title=Belle Gibson and The Whole Pantry: Is her story fact or fiction?|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-and-the-whole-pantry-is-her-story-fact-or-fiction/story-fni0dguy-1227265261138|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=The Advertiser|publisher=News Corp}}</ref> [[anti-vaccination]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Piotrowski|first1=Daniel|last2=Noble|first2=Freya|title='She pushed me not to vaccinate my kids'|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2990598/She-tried-convince-not-vaccinate-kids-Belle-Gibson-s-betrayed-former-friend-says-Pantry-founder-come-clean-truth-cancer-survival-story.html|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=Daily Mail Australia|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd}}</ref> and the consumption of non-pasteurised [[raw milk]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Andrew|last2=Cavanagh|first2=Rebekah|title=Lifestyle blogger Belle Gibson slips up on booze, milk|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/lifestyle-blogger-belle-gibson-slips-up-on-booze-milk/|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\nThe highly controversial Gerson therapy had been similarly promoted by another Australian wellness blogger, [[Jessica Ainscough]], whose funeral Gibson attended when Ainscough succumbed to cancer in late February 2015. With approximately 97% of the Australian population under seven years of age immunised, Federal [[vaccination policy]] heavily penalises parents who refuse to vaccinate their children, by denying access to significant welfare and other benefits, worth approximately $11,700 per annum. The sale of raw milk for human consumption is illegal in Australia and, in [[Victoria (state)|Victoria]], one three-year-old died and another four children under the age of five became seriously ill after consuming non-pasteurised milk in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Milman|first1=Oliver|title=Victoria launches crackdown on sale of 'raw' unpasteurised milk|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/dec/28/victoria-launches-crackdown-on-sale-of-raw-unpasteurised-milk|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable claims===\nAs Gibson's medical claims were being scrutinised, allegations emerged that charitable contributions raised in 2013 and 2014 had not been given to their intended causes.<ref name=\"theage-backlash\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|title=Backlash over app developer Belle Gibson's missing charity money|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=9 March 2015|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213648/https://www.theage.com.au/technology/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Australia|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=\"essentialbaby\">{{cite news | url=http://www.essentialbaby.com.au/life-style/current-affairs/belle-gibson-the-missing-charity-money-and-the-confounding-cancer-claims-20150310-13zsel.html | title=Belle Gibson, the missing charity money and the confounding cancer claims | work=Essential Baby | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Gibson denied the charges,<ref name=\"newscomau-refutes\">{{cite news | url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-the-whole-pantry-refutes-claims-about-charity-donations/story-fniym3t1-1227255183760 | title=Belle Gibson's The Whole Pantry refutes claims about charity donations | work=news.com.au | date=10 March 2015 | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> but [[Fairfax Media]] revealed that she had \"failed to hand over proceeds solicited in the name of five charities\" and had \"grossly overstated the company's total donations to different causes\".<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\" /> Two charities confirmed to ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper that Gibson's company had used their names in fundraising drives but had either failed to deliver the donations or had inadequately accounted for the funds.<ref name=\"erased\"/>\n\nGibson had claimed on a number of occasions in 2014 that ''The Whole Pantry'' had donated approximately $300,000 to charities, including maternal healthcare in developing nations, medical support for children with cancer, and funding schools in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/macman/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140723-ztvos.html|title=Pop into The Pantry app for a healthier lifestyle|last=Barker|first=Garry|date=July 17, 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213102/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140717-ztvos.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In late 2014, when ''The Whole Pantry'' app was pre-installed on the Apple [[iPad]], Gibson claimed through her Instagram account to be working with twenty different charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson // thewholepantry@healing_belle|url=https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|website=Populagram|publisher=Populgram, Instagram|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422174823/https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|archive-date=22 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gibson has long claimed in her [[LinkedIn]] professional networking profile, established in February 2013, to be a [[philanthropist]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson, The Whole Pantry|url=https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=30 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430210329/https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|archive-date=30 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGibson eventually admitted, in relation to fraud proceedings, that she had seriously overstated the level of charitable contributions that had been made. Subsequent media reports in March 2015 revealed that it could only be ascertained that an estimated $7,000 of the previously claimed $300,000 had been donated to a total of three charities, with at least $1,000 of the $7,000 reportedly having been donated only after Gibson became aware of the Fairfax investigation into her earlier claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150308-13xgqk.html|title=Charity money promised by 'inspirational' health app developer Belle Gibson not handed over|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|last2=Toscano|first2=NIck|date=8 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-211226/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150306-13xgqk.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Another $1,000 of the $7,000 had been donated to a charitable cause under Rothwell's name, rather than Gibson's or the company name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|title=Supporters - The ASRC Food Justice Truck - StartSomeGood: Igniting Ideas, Investment & Impact.|work=StartSomeGood|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420193743/http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2015, the parents of a young child suffering from brain cancer, whom Gibson had befriended, came forward to report that they had been unaware that Gibson had earlier been claiming to be fundraising for their child's treatment on their behalf. The family had never received any funds from her or ''The Whole Pantry'', and suspected Gibson had been using information gleaned from the family's experiences to underpin her own claims to having brain cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|title=Family of desperately ill boy fear health guru Belle Gibson used their son to bolster her cancer claims|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/family-of-desperately-ill-boy-fear-health-guru-belle-gibson-used-their-son-to-bolster-her-cancer-claims/story-fni0fit3-1227273020233|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|publisher=[[Herald Sun]], [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Concern over publisher culpability===\nAs the controversy grew, questions began to be raised about Apple, Penguin and the Australian media's lack of due diligence in ''[[prima facie]]'' accepting Gibson's claims to suffering multiple cancers, an issue taken up by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]'s ''[[Media Watch (TV program)|Media Watch]]'' program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barry|first1=Paul|title=How the media fell for Belle|url=http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s4198886.htm|website=ABC.NET.AU|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nApple Inc., in response to media enquiry in March 2015, declined to remove ''The Whole Pantry'' app from sale, stating that it was only concerned about the functionality of the app. However, ''The Whole Pantry'' was soon thereafter removed from inclusion in the Apple Watch launch. Apple subsequently deleted the app from the Apple Store, and removed it from all Apple Watch promotional material. Apple has not provided any public comment regarding the reasons behind the removal of the app,<ref>{{cite news|last=Riley|first=Duncan|title=Fake cancer survivor Belle Gibson's app pulled from App Store, still linked to Apple Watch though|url=http://siliconangle.com/blog/2015/03/17/fake-cancer-survivor-belle-gibsons-app-pulled-from-app-store-still-linked-to-apple-watch-though/|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Siliconangle.com|publisher=SiliconANGLE Media|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> but an internal email from an Australian executive to the company's US office acknowledged that the removal would be subject to comment.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nLantern Books, when initially approached by investigative journalists, claimed it had not confirmed the validity of Gibson's cancer claims as it was not required for a cookbook.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hallbaeck|first1=Jan|title=The 'hole' in the pantry story: should Penguin have validated Belle Gibson's cancer claims?|url=https://theconversation.com/the-hole-in-the-pantry-story-should-penguin-have-validated-belle-gibsons-cancer-claims-38843|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=The Conversation|publisher=The Conversation Trust|date=16 March 2015}}</ref> Soon after, as the controversy grew, Penguin withdrew the book from sale, citing a lack of response from Gibson to its queries relating to the media accusations. However, Fairfax reported that Penguin had, prior to publication of the book, already quizzed and videotaped Gibson on her cancer story, as recounted in the [[preface]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|title=Publisher Penguin pulls Belle Gibson cook book The Whole Pantry|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=16 March 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2015.05.01-005533/http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|archive-date=2015-05-01|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> Penguin agreed to pay A$30,000 to the [[Consumer Affairs Victoria|Victorian Consumer Law Fund]] as a penalty for failing to validate the factual content of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|title=Cancer-faking blogger faces legal action|date=2016-05-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''[[Elle magazine|Elle Australia]]'' magazine, published by [[Bauer Media Group]], admitted that following a laudatory December 2014 story on Gibson, they had received but ultimately dismissed anonymous claims that she was fabricating her story.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawrence|first1=Vanessa|title=What we know about Belle Gibson|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Elle Australia|publisher=Elle Australia}}</ref> A second Bauer magazine, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', which had awarded Gibson its 2014 \"Fun Fearless Female\" social media award, admitted that it too had received and dismissed a similar email.<ref name=\"honest\" /> After Gibson's confessions, the magazine decided not to strip her of the award, stating that she had been \"reader nominated and reader voted.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharp|first1=Annette|title=Cosmo defend failure to research Belle cancer claims and says she can keep Fun Fearless Female award|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/cosmo-defend-failure-to-research-belle-cancer-claims-and-says-she-can-keep-fun-fearless-female-award/story-fni0cvc9-1227318967969|accessdate=25 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=NewsCorp|date=24 April 2015}}</ref> However, a month earlier, ''Cosmopolitan''{{'}}s associate editor stated that they \"put forward the nomination myself\", indicating that the magazine {{ndash}} not the public {{ndash}} had been instrumental in promoting Gibson's award.<ref name=\"honest\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|title=An honest account of our experience with Belle Gibson|last1=Sams|first1=Lauren|date=17 March 2015|work=Cosmopolitan Australia|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091405/http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|archive-date=18 May 2015|publisher=Bauer Media Group}}</ref>\n\nA conventional cancer research professional from the [[Garvan Institute of Medical Research]] also went public to state that, by failing to conduct basic [[fact checking]] and providing \"unfiltered [[public relations|PR]]\" to Gibson's untested claims, an uncritical media had been complicit in her \"scam\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burke|first1=Liz|title='They are all complicit': Cancer researcher Dr Darren Saunders slams Belle Gibson's 'enablers'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/they-are-all-complicit-cancer-researcher-dr-darren-saunders-slams-belle-gibsons-enablers/story-fneuzlbd-1227317296471|accessdate=23 April 2015|agency=News.com.au|publisher=News Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Erasing the story===\nOnce the controversy surfaced in the media, ''The Whole Pantry'' began removing any comments made on its (since deleted) Facebook page that questioned Gibson's claims, asserting that these comments only added to \"the misinformation\" of the initial Fairfax article. This selective deletion drew even more negative comment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Jenni|title=The mystery of Belle Gibson, who claimed she cured cancer with clean living|url=http://mashable.com/2015/03/29/belle-gibson-whole-pantry/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Mashable Australia|publisher=Mashable Inc.}}</ref>\n\nSimultaneously, posts that Gibson had made on her Instagram account that made reference to her cancers or charitable donations were also selectively deleted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Does Belle Gibson Actually Have Cancer?|url=http://realitybasedmedicine.blogspot.com.au/2015/03/does-belle-gibson-actually-have-cancer.html|website=Reality Based Medicine|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> Soon after, all posts were deleted from Gibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s Instagram accounts. Around the same time, individual postings about Gibson's cancer, and claims of having died briefly while under heart surgery, were also being selectively deleted by the administrator of her blog \"at the request of a user\".<ref name=\"erased\">{{cite news|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|title=Whole Pantry founder Belle Gibson's stories of beating terminal cancer erased from internet|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/whole-pantry-founder-belle-gibsons-stories-of-beating-terminal-cancer-erased-from-internet/story-fni0fit3-1227257742137|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> Accounts across a number of social media platforms were soon either abandoned, made private, or deleted in their entirety.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Michael|first1=Sarah|last2=Dean|first2=Sarah|title=Belle Gibson's partying past reveals a love of beer, cask wine and donuts... and it's a long way from the organic regime she claims cured her 'terminal' brain cancer|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2997754/Blogger-Belle-Gibson-s-book-cancelled-U-S-wellness-empire-continues-collapse-allegations-faked-terminal-cancer.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Daily Mail Australia|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd}}</ref>\n\nGibson subsequently established another Facebook account under the alias Harry Gibson, which was made private and used to hit back at Facebook followers questioning her claims or speaking to the media.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|last2=Tuohy|first2=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson slams 'fake cancer' claims in online rant|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/health-blogger-and-app-developer-belle-gibson-hits-back-at-bullying-critics-20150315-144g0v.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\n===Admission of deceit===\nIn late April 2015, Gibson gave an interview to ''The Australian Women's Weekly'', in which she admitted to having fabricated all her cancer claims. Gibson attributed her deceit to her upbringing, and specifically to [[child neglect|neglect]] by her now-[[Family estrangement|estranged]] mother, claiming to having been forced to take care of herself and her brother since the age of 5.<ref name=\"news.com.au\">{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Rebecca|title=Belle Gibson: 'No, None of it is true'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-no-none-of-it-is-true/story-fniym874-1227315232565|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> The interview was, however, described as an admission of deceit, without expression of regret or apology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Matt|title=Nothing to like about this pretty little liar|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/nothing-to-like-about-this-pretty-little-liar/story-fni0ffsx-1227320920457|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp Ltd|date=25 April 2015}}</ref> In a May 2015 interview with the same magazine, Gibson's mother Natalie Dal-Bello refuted several claims Gibson had made about her family, including the false claim that her brother was [[autism|autistic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson's mum slams troubled childhood claims as 'a lot of rubbish'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-mum-slams-troubled-childhood-claims-as-a-lot-of-rubbish/story-fneuz9ev-1227358455303|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> Gibson's ''Women's Weekly'' interview was arranged by [[Bespoke Approach]], and Gibson was provided ''[[pro bono]]'' representation by the company during the interview.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/strewth/toil-for-the-belle/news-story/5be985d1f1b73c1a0fda7dab453ffab1|title=Toil for the Belle|last1=Jeffrey|first1=James|date=23 April 2015|work=The Australian|accessdate=25 April 2015|url-status=live|publisher=NewsCorp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Gibson was rumoured to have received A$45,000 for an interview with [[Nine Network]]'s ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|title=Belle Gibson promises to tell the whole truth: \u2018I have lost everything\u2019|last=Willis|first=Charlotte|date=2015-06-25|website=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Corp Australia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003193353/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|archive-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/broadcast/nine-network-faces-backlash-over-60-minutes-interview-with-belle-gibson/news-story/311065149cfe5289ea2b4d3af6ef283d|title=Nine Network faces backlash over 60 Minutes interview with Belle Gibson|last=Guilliatt|first=Richard|date=25 Jun 2015|work=The Australian|publisher=News Corp|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-date=|access-date=24 Jun 2017}}</ref> Stefanie Spinks of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' wrote that \"by accepting $45,000 for her interview, Belle is sending the message that people can profit off stealing, lying and taking advantage of people's good intentions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3138530/This-absolute-disgrace-Thousands-former-Belle-Gibson-supporters-sign-online-petition-demanding-cancer-fraud-donate-fee-upcoming-interview-charity.html|title=Thousands of former Belle Gibson supporters sign online petition demanding the cancer fraud donate any fee from upcoming interview to charity|work=Daily Mail|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> During this interview, Gibson claimed to have been visited at home by a doctor named Mark Johns who had a portable, German-made electronic machine with paddles and lights that diagnosed her cancers. She also claimed that she believed she was taking [[oral chemotherapy]] prescribed by this same doctor. No one has found any trace of this person nor any information on the machine that was used to make a diagnosis.\n\n===Legal action===\n\nConsumer Affairs Victoria brought legal action against Gibson for allegedly breaking Australian consumer law. The regulator said it had conducted an in-depth investigation of Gibson's activities and applied to Australia's Federal Court for leave to pursue legal action. Gibson's publisher, Penguin Australia, has already agreed to pay A$30,000 (US$22,200; \u00a315,300) to the Victorian Consumer Law Fund as a penalty for releasing The Whole Pantry, which was not fact checked.<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson: Australian blogger who faked cancer faces legal action|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2017, Federal Court Justice [[Debra Mortimer]] delivered the decision that \"most but not all\" of the claims were proven. Gibson did not appear in court for the decision. Justice Mortimer found that Gibson's claims had been misleading and deceptive, and that \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer from the time she began making these claims in public to promote ''The Whole Pantry Book'' and the apps in mid-2013\", but there was not enough evidence to prove that she was not acting out of delusion.<ref name=\"judgement\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2017/03/15/06/22/belle-gibsons-judgement-to-be-handed-down-in-court|title=Disgraced wellness blogger Belle Gibson facing more than $1 million in fines|date=15 March 2017|work=9 News|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 FCA 240\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|240|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson |date=15 March 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref name=\"fad\"/>\n\nIn September 2017, Gibson was fined A$410,000 (US$310,000; \u00a3240,000) for making false claims about her donations to charity.<ref name=\"2017 FCA 1148\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|1148|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson (No 3) |date=28 September 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Karen |last=Percy |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-28/disgraced-wellness-blogger-belle-gibson-fined/8995500 |title=Fake wellness blogger Belle Gibson fined over cancer claims |date=28 September 2017 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission}}</ref> {{As of|2019|04}}, Gibson had not yet paid the fine, and authorities were seeking power to charge her with [[contempt of court]]. A new trial was set for 14 May  and she faced an undetermined number of years in jail if she did not attend.<ref>{{cite news |title=Belle Gibson faces jail time if $410k fine for cancer fraud goes unpaid |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-27/belle-gibson-faces-jail-term-for-unpaid-cancer-fraud-fine/10558150 |date=28 November 2018 |access-date=28 November 2018 |last=Oaten |first=James |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson to explain why she hasn\u2019t paid $410k fine for duping sick Aussies|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/belle-gibson-to-explain-why-she-hasnt-paid-410k-fine-for-duping-sick-aussies/news-story/43c24e05cb91d5b6f74f3aa2e26b392c|date=17 April 2019|access-date=18 April 2019|publisher=news.com.au}}</ref> As of mid-September 2019, Gibson still had not paid, claiming to be broke, and Consumer Affairs Victoria were still seeking to enforce the penalty.<ref>\"Belle Gibson 'in hiding'\". The Daily Telegraph (Australia), 15 Sep 2019, p. 11</ref> In a 2017 letter later released by the Federal Court, Gibson had stated that she was $170,000 in debt, and had $5,000 to her name.<ref name=\"letter\" />\n\n==House raid by police==\nOn 22 January 2020, the Sheriff\u2019s Office of Victoria  raided Gibson's home in Northcote and seized items to recoup Gibson's unpaid fines,<ref name=\"raided\"/> which, due to interest and costs, exceeded half a million dollars.<ref name=\"sheriff\"/>\n\n==Claimed adoption into Oromo community==\nOn 23 January 2020, a Shabo Media video from October 2019 surfaced in which Gibson was wearing a headscarf and speaking partially in [[Oromo language]] (referring to herself as \"Sanbotu\"), discussing the political situation in [[Ethiopia]] with an interviewer and referring to Ethiopia as \"back home\". She professed to have been adopted by the Ethiopian community in Melbourne after volunteering for four years, calling the adoption a gift from \"Allah\".<ref name=\"adopted\"/><ref name=\"community\"/>\n\nHowever, on the same day, the president of the Australian Oromo Community Association in Victoria, Tarekegn Chimdi, stated that Gibson was not a registered volunteer, \"is not a community member and she\u2019s also not working with the community,\" and that he had only seen her at events two or three times. He expressed that nobody seemed to know who she was and he had only just learnt of her backstory, and expressed a desire for her to stop saying she is part of the community.<ref name=\"rejected\"/><ref name=\"Melbourne\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ashley Kirilow]], a Canadian fraudster who raised money for cancer charities by falsely claiming that she had cancer\n*[[Michael Guglielmucci]], an Australian singer who claimed to have cancer to boost his performing career\n*[[Diet and cancer]]\n*[[Munchausen syndrome]] <ref name=\"sickness\"/><ref name=\"munchausen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"letter\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|title=2017 letter Belle Gibson wrote detailing debts released|date=2020-02-18|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050632/https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|archive-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"munchausen\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|title=Munchausen syndrome: Why bloggers like cancer fraud Belle Gibson fake sickness online|last=Nianias|first=Helen|date=2015-04-30|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent Digital News & Media Ltd|location=UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428224900/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|archive-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Melbourne\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|title=Belle Gibson has been adopted by Ethiopian community in Melbourne|last=Smith|first=Rohan|date=2020-01-24|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126195951/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"fad\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|title=Belle Gibson backs new health fad ahead of court judgment|last=Cavanagh|first=Rebekah|date=15 March 2017|work=Herald Sun|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-125528/https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"community\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|title=Belle Gibson 'adopted' by Ethiopian community|last=Kinsella|first=Elise|date=2020-01-23|work=ABC News|location=Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126203125/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|title=Apple exposed over Belle Gibson affair|last1=Toscano|first1=Nick|date=19 November 2017|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223125/https://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"The Australian\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/story-e6frg8zx-1227255933051|title=Mega-blogger Belle Gibson casts doubt on her own cancer claims|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|date=10 March 2015|newspaper=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/2017.01.26-011131/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/megablogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/news-story/de179f2f17de51d1071096eb7bd2bdee|archive-date=2017-01-26|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rejected\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|title=Cancer fraudster rejected by Ethiopians|last=Akerman|first=Tessa|date=24 January 2020|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-132450/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"adopted\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|title=Cancer fraudster Belle Gibson \u2018adopted\u2019 by Ethiopian community|date=January 23, 2020|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123132020/https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|archive-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sheriff\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|title=Sheriff raids cancer fraudster Belle Gibson's home over unpaid fine|last=AAP|date=2020-01-22|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122215711/https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|archive-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"raided\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|title=Belle Gibson\u2019s home raided by sheriff over cancer fraud fine|last=Urban|first=Rebecca|date=2020-01-22|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-210004/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150314032024/http://thewholepantryapp.com/ The Whole Pantry website], registered by Gibson\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Belle}}\n[[Category:Australian fraudsters]]\n[[Category:Health fraud]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:People from Launceston, Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Alternative cancer treatment advocates]]\n[[Category:Confidence tricksters]]\n[[Category:Medical controversies in Australia]]\n[[Category:People convicted for health fraud]]\n", "name_user": "SebastianDrawsStuff", "label": "safe", "comment": "Made edited to location links on the inset and introductory paragraph.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belle_Gibson"}
{"title_page": "Cannabis in North Dakota", "text_new": "'''Cannabis in North Dakota''' concerns the [[Cannabis (drug)|drug cannabis]] in [[North Dakota]], [[United States]], where cannabis was legalized for medical purposes in 2016 but remains illegal for recreational purposes. Possession of small recreational amounts is a [[misdemeanor]] crime.<ref>[http://norml.org/laws/item/north-dakota-penalties-2 North Dakota Laws & Penalties], NORML</ref> The cultivation of [[hemp]] is currently legal in North Dakota.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cannabisnews.com/news/15/thread15717.shtml|title=Revolution, Hemp Style Now|publisher=Cannabis News}}</ref> In November 2018, the state's voters voted on recreational marijuana legalization, along with [[Cannabis in Michigan|Michigan]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tomangell/2018/08/13/north-dakota-marijuana-legalization-measure-qualifies-for-november-ballot/|title=North Dakota Marijuana Legalization Measure Qualifies For November Ballot|first=Tom|last=Angell|website=Forbes}}</ref> the measure was rejected 59% to 41%.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/north-dakota-voters-reject-marijuana-legalization-measure/|title=North Dakota Voters Reject Marijuana Legalization Measure|first=Kyle|last=Jaeger|date=7 November 2018|publisher=}}</ref>Two groups are putting marijuana legalization on the June 2020 Primary and the November 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Alexander |url=https://www.jamestownsun.com/news/government-and-politics/4043482-Two-groups-fighting-for-legal-marijuana-in-ND |website=Jamestown Sun |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Prohibition==\n[[Marijuana]] was made illegal in North Dakota in 1933; [[Oklahoma]] made it illegal the same year, and South Dakota in 1931.<ref name=\"Whitebread1974\">{{cite book|author=Charles H. Whitebread|title=The Marijuana Conviction: A History of Marijuana Prohibition in the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0DVtoQlvZs0C|year=1974|publisher=Lindesmith Center|isbn=978-1-891385-06-3|page=39}}</ref> In May 2019, penalties were in the state, with possession resulting in a fine instead of jail time, however possession of any amount of hashish or concentrates is still a felony, with punishment up to 5 years in prison.\n\n==Medical marijuana ==\n===Failed attempts (2015)===\nIn 2015, House Bill 1430 attempted to establish a medical marijuana framework, but was voted down at 26-67 in February. Members of the House [[Human services|Human Services]] Committee stated: \u201cWe just felt that the concerns and the risks at this point in time outweigh the potential benefits \u2026 for a small group that feels that none of the currently available drugs work\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Nowatzki |first=Mike |url=http://www.grandforksherald.com/news/region/3682042-north-dakota-house-kills-medical-marijuana-bill |title=North Dakota House kills medical marijuana bill |publisher=Grand Forks Herald |date=2015-02-18 |accessdate=2015-08-26}}</ref> Following the bill's failure, [[Fargo, North Dakota|Fargo]] resident [[Rilie Ray Morgan]] began the process of preparing a ballot initiative to legalize medical marijuana for the 2016 general election.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicole Johnson |url=http://www.valleynewslive.com/home/headlines/Fargo-Man-Fighting-To-Legalize-Medical-Marijuana-In-ND--322335781.html |title=Fargo Man Fighting To Legalize Medical Marijuana In ND, \"Be Compassionate\" |publisher=Valleynewslive.com |date=2015-08-19 |accessdate=2015-08-26}}</ref>\n\n===Medical legalization (2016)===\nIn 2016, North Dakota voters approved Measure 5, establishing a medical cannabis program for their state.<ref>{{cite web|last=New |first=The |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-dakota-ballot-measure-5-medical-marijuana |title=North Dakota Measure 5 \u2014 Medical Marijuana \u2014 Results: Approved \u2013 Election Results 2016 \u2013 The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2016-11-08 |accessdate=2016-11-17}}</ref> In 2017, both houses of the state legislature passed changes to Measure 5, including removal of a provision allowing medical users to grow their own marijuana. The changes also required that a medical professional specifically recommend smoking as a method of using marijuana in some cases. Some backers of the ballot initiative were displeased with the legislation, saying that some of the regulations were not justifiable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/north-dakota/articles/2017-04-13/north-dakota-lawmakers-approve-medical-marijuana-regulations|title=Rules Set for North Dakota Medical Marijuana Program|publisher=US News|accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref> The bill passed both houses of the ND State Legislature with the required two-thirds majority. As of July 10, 2018, the [[North Dakota Department of Health]] has opened an application window for medical cannabis dispensary licenses in the Bismarck and Fargo areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndhealth.gov/MM/PDF/Status_Update/Status_Update_7.03.18.pdf |title=Medical Marijuana Program Status Update 07-10-18}}</ref>\n\n===Medical Marijuana Program===\nEffective April 18, 2017, the North Dakota Department of Health established and implemented a medical marijuana program to allow the production, processing, sale, dispensing, and medical use of marijuana by qualifying patients and caregivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndhealth.gov/MM/|title=Medical Marijuana - North Dakota Department of Health|website=www.ndhealth.gov}}</ref> In May 2018, [[Pure Dakota LLC]] and [[Grassroots Cannabis]] were selected to run the two manufacturing facilities allowed under the program's rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kfyrtv.com/content/news/ND-Department-of-Health-chooses-medical-marijuana-manufacturers-482841451.html|title=ND Department of Health chooses medical marijuana manufacturers|first=Andrew|last=Horn|website=www.kfyrtv.com}}</ref>\n\n==Failed recreational referendum==\nNorth Dakota residents voted on an initiative to legalise recreational marijuana at the same time as the 2018 midterms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/11/6/18052874/north-dakota-measure-3-marijuana-legalization-results|title=North Dakota votes against marijuana legalization, rejecting Measure 3|website=www.vox.com}}</ref>  The measure was rejected 59% to 41%.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Polling==\nA late-2014 poll conducted by the [[University of North Dakota]] found that North Dakotans favored medical marijuana 47-41, but were against legalizing recreational marijuana, 24-68.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/state-and-regional/poll-n-d-accepts-medical-marijuana-not-recreational/article_55de99e8-567b-11e4-9b12-6f5267f9b24a.html |title=Poll: N.D. accepts medical marijuana, not recreational |publisher=Bismarcktribune.com |date=2014-10-17 |accessdate=2015-08-26}}</ref> A 2018 poll showed that North Dakotans favored the recreational marijuana ballot initiative 46-39 with 15 percent undecided.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/07/11/next-state-legalize-marijuana-could-be-north-dakota/?noredirect=on |title=The next state to legalize marijuana could be . . . North Dakota?}}</ref>\n\n==Legislation==\nPersonal use possession of less than half an ounce is an infraction and you can not be imprisoned. However, there is a maximum fine of $1,000. Personal use possession of less than half an ounce while operating a motor vehicle is a Class A misdemeanor punishable by a maximum sentence of 1 year imprisonment and a maximum fine of $1,000. Personal use possession of half an ounce - 1 ounce is a Class A misdemeanor punishable by a maximum sentence of 1 year imprisonment and a maximum fine of $1,000.<ref>[normal.org]</ref>\n\nCurrently a Petition is circulating for signatures called the ND For Freedom of Cannabis Act <ref>https://vip.sos.nd.gov/pdfs/Measures%20Info/Petitions%20Being%20Circulated/approved%20copy%20of%20petition.pdf</ref>. If the petition is successful in getting 26,904 Signatures from North Dakota voters it will be placed on the next election ballot <ref>https://vip.sos.nd.gov/pdfs/Measures%20Info/Petitions%20Being%20Circulated/Article%20I%20Timeline.pdf</ref>. If passed it would allow anyone over the age of 21 to possess, grow, process, or transport 12 cannabis plants for personal use.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cannabis in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Cannabis in North Dakota| ]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cannabis in North Dakota''' concerns the [[Cannabis (drug)|drug cannabis]] in [[North Dakota]], [[United States]], where cannabis was legalized for medical purposes in 2016 but remains illegal for recreational purposes. Possession of small recreational amounts is a [[misdemeanor]] crime.<ref>[http://norml.org/laws/item/north-dakota-penalties-2 North Dakota Laws & Penalties], NORML</ref> The cultivation of [[hemp]] is currently legal in North Dakota.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cannabisnews.com/news/15/thread15717.shtml|title=Revolution, Hemp Style Now|publisher=Cannabis News}}</ref> In November 2018, the state's voters voted on recreational marijuana legalization, along with [[Cannabis in Michigan|Michigan]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tomangell/2018/08/13/north-dakota-marijuana-legalization-measure-qualifies-for-november-ballot/|title=North Dakota Marijuana Legalization Measure Qualifies For November Ballot|first=Tom|last=Angell|website=Forbes}}</ref> the measure was rejected 59% to 41%.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/north-dakota-voters-reject-marijuana-legalization-measure/|title=North Dakota Voters Reject Marijuana Legalization Measure|first=Kyle|last=Jaeger|date=7 November 2018|publisher=}}</ref>Two groups are putting marijuana legalization on the June 2020 Primary and the November 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Alexander |url=https://www.jamestownsun.com/news/government-and-politics/4043482-Two-groups-fighting-for-legal-marijuana-in-ND |website=Jamestown Sun |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Prohibition==\n[[Marijuana]] was made illegal in North Dakota in 1933; [[Oklahoma]] made it illegal the same year, and South Dakota in 1931.<ref name=\"Whitebread1974\">{{cite book|author=Charles H. Whitebread|title=The Marijuana Conviction: A History of Marijuana Prohibition in the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0DVtoQlvZs0C|year=1974|publisher=Lindesmith Center|isbn=978-1-891385-06-3|page=39}}</ref> In May 2019, penalties were in the state, with possession resulting in a fine instead of jail time, however possession of any amount of hashish or concentrates is still a felony, with punishment up to 5 years in prison.\n\n==Medical marijuana ==\n===Failed attempts (2015)===\nIn 2015, House Bill 1430 attempted to establish a medical marijuana framework, but was voted down at 26-67 in February. Members of the House [[Human services|Human Services]] Committee stated: \u201cWe just felt that the concerns and the risks at this point in time outweigh the potential benefits \u2026 for a small group that feels that none of the currently available drugs work\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Nowatzki |first=Mike |url=http://www.grandforksherald.com/news/region/3682042-north-dakota-house-kills-medical-marijuana-bill |title=North Dakota House kills medical marijuana bill |publisher=Grand Forks Herald |date=2015-02-18 |accessdate=2015-08-26}}</ref> Following the bill's failure, [[Fargo, North Dakota|Fargo]] resident [[Rilie Ray Morgan]] began the process of preparing a ballot initiative to legalize medical marijuana for the 2016 general election.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicole Johnson |url=http://www.valleynewslive.com/home/headlines/Fargo-Man-Fighting-To-Legalize-Medical-Marijuana-In-ND--322335781.html |title=Fargo Man Fighting To Legalize Medical Marijuana In ND, \"Be Compassionate\" |publisher=Valleynewslive.com |date=2015-08-19 |accessdate=2015-08-26}}</ref>\n\n===Medical legalization (2016)===\nIn 2016, North Dakota voters approved Measure 5, establishing a medical cannabis program for their state.<ref>{{cite web|last=New |first=The |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-dakota-ballot-measure-5-medical-marijuana |title=North Dakota Measure 5 \u2014 Medical Marijuana \u2014 Results: Approved \u2013 Election Results 2016 \u2013 The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2016-11-08 |accessdate=2016-11-17}}</ref> In 2017, both houses of the state legislature passed changes to Measure 5, including removal of a provision allowing medical users to grow their own marijuana. The changes also required that a medical professional specifically recommend smoking as a method of using marijuana in some cases. Some backers of the ballot initiative were displeased with the legislation, saying that some of the regulations were not justifiable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/north-dakota/articles/2017-04-13/north-dakota-lawmakers-approve-medical-marijuana-regulations|title=Rules Set for North Dakota Medical Marijuana Program|publisher=US News|accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref> The bill passed both houses of the ND State Legislature with the required two-thirds majority. As of July 10, 2018, the [[North Dakota Department of Health]] has opened an application window for medical cannabis dispensary licenses in the Bismarck and Fargo areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndhealth.gov/MM/PDF/Status_Update/Status_Update_7.03.18.pdf |title=Medical Marijuana Program Status Update 07-10-18}}</ref>\n\n===Medical Marijuana Program===\nEffective April 18, 2017, the North Dakota Department of Health established and implemented a medical marijuana program to allow the production, processing, sale, dispensing, and medical use of marijuana by qualifying patients and caregivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndhealth.gov/MM/|title=Medical Marijuana - North Dakota Department of Health|website=www.ndhealth.gov}}</ref> In May 2018, [[Pure Dakota LLC]] and [[Grassroots Cannabis]] were selected to run the two manufacturing facilities allowed under the program's rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kfyrtv.com/content/news/ND-Department-of-Health-chooses-medical-marijuana-manufacturers-482841451.html|title=ND Department of Health chooses medical marijuana manufacturers|first=Andrew|last=Horn|website=www.kfyrtv.com}}</ref>\n\n==Failed recreational referendum==\nNorth Dakota residents voted on an initiative to legalise recreational marijuana at the same time as the 2018 midterms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/11/6/18052874/north-dakota-measure-3-marijuana-legalization-results|title=North Dakota votes against marijuana legalization, rejecting Measure 3|website=www.vox.com}}</ref>  The measure was rejected 59% to 41%.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Polling==\nA late-2014 poll conducted by the [[University of North Dakota]] found that North Dakotans favored medical marijuana 47-41, but were against legalizing recreational marijuana, 24-68.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/state-and-regional/poll-n-d-accepts-medical-marijuana-not-recreational/article_55de99e8-567b-11e4-9b12-6f5267f9b24a.html |title=Poll: N.D. accepts medical marijuana, not recreational |publisher=Bismarcktribune.com |date=2014-10-17 |accessdate=2015-08-26}}</ref> A 2018 poll showed that North Dakotans favored the recreational marijuana ballot initiative 46-39 with 15 percent undecided.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/07/11/next-state-legalize-marijuana-could-be-north-dakota/?noredirect=on |title=The next state to legalize marijuana could be . . . North Dakota?}}</ref>\n\n==Legislation==\nPersonal use possession of less than half an ounce is a Class B [[misdemeanor]] punishable by a maximum sentence of 30 days imprisonment and a maximum fine of $1,000. Personal use possession of less than half an ounce while operating a motor vehicle is a Class A misdemeanor punishable by a maximum sentence of 1 year imprisonment and a maximum fine of $1,000. Personal use possession of half an ounce - 1 ounce is a Class A misdemeanor punishable by a maximum sentence of 1 year imprisonment and a maximum fine of $1,000.<ref>[normal.org]</ref>\n\nCurrently a Petition is circulating for signatures called the ND For Freedom of Cannabis Act <ref>https://vip.sos.nd.gov/pdfs/Measures%20Info/Petitions%20Being%20Circulated/approved%20copy%20of%20petition.pdf</ref>. If the petition is successful in getting 26,904 Signatures from North Dakota voters it will be placed on the next election ballot <ref>https://vip.sos.nd.gov/pdfs/Measures%20Info/Petitions%20Being%20Circulated/Article%20I%20Timeline.pdf</ref>. If passed it would allow anyone over the age of 21 to possess, grow, process, or transport 12 cannabis plants for personal use.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cannabis in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Cannabis in North Dakota| ]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1014:b116:2842:8d3b:403c:5a89:fda5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLegislation:I fixed one minor detail about North Dakota\u2019s legislation about possession under half and ounce in the state.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannabis_in_North_Dakota"}
{"title_page": "Chicken (dance)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Chicken Dance}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}\nThe '''Chicken''' is a popular [[rhythm and blues]] [[dance]] that started in [[Americas|America]] in the 1950s, in which the dancers flapped their [[arm]]s and kicked back their [[Foot|feet]] in an imitation of a [[chicken]].  The dance featured lateral [[Dance move|body movements]].  It was used primarily as a change of pace step while doing the [[Twist (dance)|twist]]. The chicken dance gained popularity when [[Rufus Thomas]] wrote \"[[Do the Funky Chicken]]\", a hit record in 1970.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the 1960s, i dont care about this entry at all. the Chicken gave rise to [[The Frug]], showcased in [[Bob Fosse]]'s choreography.<ref name=\"Smith2010\">{{cite book|author=Karen Lynn Smith|title=Popular Dance: From Ballroom to Hip-hop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2inCRlYF-iAC&pg=PA137|year=2010|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-3476-5|pages=137\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is featured sdsd in the 1980s original ''[[The Blues Brothers (film)|Blues Brothers]]'' [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[John Landis]] and starring [[John Belushi]] and [[Dan Aykroyd]].\n\nIt is mentioned in 1997 Chicago Tribune column \"Advice, like youth, probably just wasted on the young\"<ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/columnists/chi-schmich-sunscreen-column-column.html Advice, like youth, probably just wasted on the young]. Chicago Tribune (1997-06-01). Retrieved on 2017-07-27.</ref> by [[Mary Schmich]], and in 1999 was made into a well-known song by [[Baz Luhrmann]] titled \"[[Wear Sunscreen]]\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicken}}\n[[Category:Dances of the United States]]\n[[Category:1950s in the United States]]\n\n\n{{Dance-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Chicken Dance}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}\nThe '''Chicken''' is a popular [[rhythm and blues]] [[dance]] that started in [[Americas|America]] in the 1950s, in which the dancers flapped their [[arm]]s and kicked back their [[Foot|feet]] in an imitation of a [[chicken]].  The dance featured lateral [[Dance move|body movements]].  It was used primarily as a change of pace step while doing the [[Twist (dance)|twist]]. The chicken dance gained popularity when [[Rufus Thomas]] wrote \"[[Do the Funky Chicken]]\", a hit record in 1970.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the 1960s the Chicken gave rise to [[The Frug]], showcased in [[Bob Fosse]]'s choreography.<ref name=\"Smith2010\">{{cite book|author=Karen Lynn Smith|title=Popular Dance: From Ballroom to Hip-hop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2inCRlYF-iAC&pg=PA137|year=2010|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-3476-5|pages=137\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is featured in the 1980s original ''[[The Blues Brothers (film)|Blues Brothers]]'' [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[John Landis]] and starring [[John Belushi]] and [[Dan Aykroyd]].\n\nIt is mentioned in 1997 Chicago Tribune column \"Advice, like youth, probably just wasted on the young\"<ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/columnists/chi-schmich-sunscreen-column-column.html Advice, like youth, probably just wasted on the young]. Chicago Tribune (1997-06-01). Retrieved on 2017-07-27.</ref> by [[Mary Schmich]], and in 1999 was made into a well-known song by [[Baz Luhrmann]] titled \"[[Wear Sunscreen]]\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicken}}\n[[Category:Dances of the United States]]\n[[Category:1950s in the United States]]\n\n\n{{Dance-stub}}\n", "name_user": "120.147.214.12", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLegacy)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicken_(dance)"}
